]] of the Burkes of County Mayo, Burke was a son of Richard an Fhorbhair mac William de Burgh, a natural son of William Laith de Burgh, who was a son of [[Richard \u00d3g de Burgh]], illegitimate son of William de Burgh (d. 1205) original founder of the de Burgh/Burke dynasty in Ireland.<ref name=\"blake_1911\">{{cite journal | journal=Journal of the Galway Archaeological and Historical Society | volume=VII | title=Notes on the Persons Named in the Obituary Book of the Franciscan Abbey at Galway | first=Martin J | last=Blake | author-link1=Martin J. Blake | issue=1 | pages=1-28 | year=1911 | url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~nolenancestry/notes_on_the_persons_named_in_the_obituary_book_of_the_franciscan_abbey_at_galway.rtf | accessdate=2006-11-28 |jstor = 25535068}}, p.10 </ref>  The same descent is given by [[Duald MacFirbis]] in his ''[[Leabhar na nGenealach]]'' (Book of the Genealogies), mostly compiled in 1649-50, and its revised abridgement the ''[[Cuimre na nGenealach]]'' (Binding of the Genealogies) of 1666.<ref name=\"blake_1911\" /> This is the ancestry presented by [[John O'Hart]] in his ''Irish pedigrees; or, The origin and stem of the Irish nation'' (1876),<ref>John O'Hart (1892), ''Irish pedigrees; or, The origin and stem of the Irish nation'', 5th ed. ([https://www.libraryireland.com/Pedigrees2/burke.php extract])</ref> and in the Oxford ''A New History of Ireland'' (1984), where the authors write  \"The origins of the Clanricard line are not absolutely proven, but the descent given is that in the best Irish genealogical sources and is not contradicted by contemporary sources.\"<ref>T. W. Moody, F. X. Martin, and F. J. Byrne, eds. (1984), ''A New History of Ireland Volume IX - Maps, Genealogies, Lists: A Companion to Irish History, Part II''. [[Oxford University Press]], p.&nbsp;170.</ref>  This volume has been used as the basis for the family tree below.\n\nOn this view, Burke would have been the leader of an illegitimate branch of the de Burgh family that were already strong in south Connaught, and were able to use the confict of the 1330s to establish themselves as an independent lordship.  The name \"Clanricarde\", first recorded in 1335, would reflect their ancestry from [[Richard \u00d3g de Burgh]], and might have already been in informal use for a number of generations.\n\nHowever, as noted by [[Martin J. Blake]] in 1911,<ref name=\"blake_1911\" /> the pedigree above is not without its problems.  In particular, William Liath de Burgh, the founder of the Franciscan Abbey in Galway, is known to have died in 1324. As Blake writes \"it is obvious, having regard to these dates, that he could hardly have been a grandson (as these writers represent him to be) of the first William de Burgh in Ireland, who died early in A.D. 1206 as the English State Records prove.\"  The MacFirbis pedigree also omits Burke's successor Richard \u00d3g Burke, whose existence is well attested.  Blake concludes that MacFirbis and the earlier manuscript \"are accurate as regards the genealogy they give of the Mac William Bourkes of Mayo (Mac William Eighter) but that they had no accurate information regarding the early part of the pedigree of the Mac William Burkes of Clan-Ricard (Mac William Oughter) and could only make a guess at it\u2013with the not surprising result, that they made a mess of it.\"<ref name=\"blake_1911\" />\n\nA different ancestry for Burke was given by [[John Lodge (archivist)|John Lodge]] in his ''Peerage of Ireland'' (2nd ed, 1789),<ref>[[John Lodge (archivist)|John Lodge]] and [[Mervyn Archdall (Irish antiquary)|Mervyn Archdall]] (1789) ''The peerage of Ireland: or, A genealogical history of the present nobility of that kingdom'', 2nd edition. Vol 1, p. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H0sTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127 127].<br />The information then also appeared in various derived and knock-off works, such as W. Owen (1790), ''The Peerage of England, Scotland, and Ireland. Volume III: The peerage of Ireland'', p. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zjAwAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA9 9]<br />Compare also eg [[James Hardiman]] (1820), ''The History of the Town and County of the Town of Galway'', p. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MuA1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54 54]<br />Lodge had also prepared a history of the Burkes for the first edition of his book (1754), but it was withdrawn \"at the Desire of the Right Honourable the Earl of Clanrickard\". (1st edition, p. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=o5FcAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71 71])</ref> and followed by [[Edmund Lodge]] in his ''Genealogy of the Existing British Peerage'' (1832).<ref>[[Edmund Lodge]] (1832), ''Genealogy of the Existing British Peerage'', p. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QK-4tHp4dzgC&pg=PA78&lpg=PA78 78]<br />The ancestry also appears in other reference works of this period, for example George Crabb (1833), ''Universal historical dictionary'', Vol. I, p. [https://archive.org/details/universalhistori10crab/page/n523/mode/1up 524]</ref>  \n\nAccording to this version William Liath de Burgh was identical with the William de Burgh who was the son of [[William \u00d3g de Burgh]], that died at the [[Battle of \u00c1th an gCeap]] in 1270,<ref>cf also the [[Annals of the Four Masters]], which contain the record that \"William Liath Burke, son of William Mor, died\".</ref> and father of [[Walter Liath de Burgh]], whose starving to death in 1332 triggered the Burke civil war.  On this view William Liath de Burgh was the dominant Anglo-Norman noble in all Connaught, second in authority only to his cousin [[Richard \u00d3g de Burgh, 2nd Earl of Ulster]] among the de Burghs.  Ulick de Burgh is presented as the son of William Liath de Burgh, and so brother to [[Edmond Albanach de Burgh]] and Walter de Burgh, with Ulick and Edmond ultimately partitioning Connaught between themselves at the end of the conflict as brothers.  Blake asserts that the Burke who was a son of Richard an Fhorbhair should be identified with [[Ulick Burke of Umhaill]], ancestor of the Bourkes of the Owles, in County Mayo.<ref name=\"blake_1911\" />\n\n==The First ''Clanricarde''==\n\nOn the death of [[Richard \u00d3g de Burgh, 2nd Earl of Ulster]] in 1326, the earldom passed to his grandson [[William Donn de Burgh, 3rd Earl of Ulster]], then 14 years old.  William became increasingly estranged and suspicious of his two principal lieutenants, Henry de Mandeville in Ulster and Walter de Burgh in Connaught.  In 1331 he had Henry de Mandeville arrested, and the following year he had Walter de Burgh with two of his brothers captured and imprisoned. He then ordered that Walter should be starved to death.  [[Gylle de Burgh]], the sister of Walter and wife of Robert de Mandeville, Henry's brother, plotted revenge and in June 1333 the young Earl was cut down as he passed through [[Carrickfergus]] by members of his own retinue, members and associates of the de Mandeville family.\n\nThis action triggered [[Burke Civil War|open civil war]] between the different branches of the de Burgh family. The Earl's heir-general, his infant daughter, [[Elizabeth de Burgh, 4th Countess of Ulster]], was taken to England on her father's death and lost control over her lands. Warfare broke out among the [[Gaels|Gaelic]]-[[Irish people|Irish]] tenants of the late Earl \u2013 many of whom expelled the [[Anglo-Irish]] \u2013 and among the three principal members of the de Burgh family:\n\n* [[Edmond de Burgh]] of [[Castleconnell]] (now in [[County Limerick]]), surviving brother of the second Earl, senior member of the Earl's direct family.\n* [[Edmond Albanach de Burgh]] of north [[Connacht]] (mainly [[County Mayo]])\n* Ulick Burke of Annaghkeen in south Connacht (mainly east [[County Galway]])\n\nA series of raids and counter-raids ensued, with Edmond de Burgh reportedly laying waste much of Connaught in 1335.  But in 1338 Edmond de Burgh was cornered and caught at [[Ballinrobe]] by his cousin Edmond Albanach, who according to the [[Annals of the Four Masters]] \"fastened a stone to his neck and drowned him in [[Lough Mask]]\".\n\nIn the aftermath by 1340 the much weakened family had divided into three separate, independent lordships:\n\n* [[Clanwilliam (County Limerick)|Clanwilliam]] Burke of [[County Limerick]]\n* [[Mac William \u00cdochtar]] of [[County Mayo]]\n* [[Clanricarde]] of [[County Galway]]\n\nUlick remained Clanricarde until his death in 1343 (or 1353 ?<ref name=\"blake_1911\" />), to be succeeded by his son, [[Richard \u00d3g Burke]].\n\nHe is said to have possessed an unusual nickname \u2014 ''Bod-an-Balcuigh'', which translated to \"Penis of Power\".{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Family tree==\n(based on the Oxford ''A New History of Ireland'', volume IX, (1984)).\n\n   Walter de Burgh\n   |\n   |____________________________________________\n   |                                           |\n   |                                           |\n  [[William de Burgh]], died 1205.    [[Hubert de Burgh, 1st Earl of Kent]], d. 1243. \n   |                                        (issue; John and Hubert)\n   |_________________________________________________________________________________________________________\n   |                                                         |                                             |\n   |                                                         |                                             |    \n  [[Richard M\u00f3r de Burgh, 1st Baron of Connaught]]  [[Hubert de Burgh, Bishop of Limerick]], d. 1250.   [[Richard \u00d3ge de Burgh]]\n   |                                                                                                       |\n   |                                           ____________________________________________________________|\n  de Burgh [[Earl of Ulster]],                     |                  |               |\n  Burke of [[Castleconnell]], [[County Limerick]]      |                  |               |\n  [[Mac William Iochtar]] Bourke of [[County Mayo]].  Hubert           William            Richard                                  \n                                               |                  |               |\n                                               |                  |               |_________________               \n                                      Clan Mac Hubert?   Richard an Fhorbhair     |                |\n                                                                  |               |                |\n   _______________________________________________________________|               Sir David Donn  Sir William Ruad\n   |                                           |         |                            |                    d.1327.\n   |                                           |         |                   Clan Mac David\n   [[Ulick Burke of Annaghkeen]], d. 1343.     Raymond  Walter \u00d3ge\n   |\n   |____________________________________\n   |                                  |\n   |                                  |  \n   [[Richard \u00d3g Burke]], d. 1387.     Edmund, d. 1410\n   |\n   |___________________________________________________\n   |                                                  |\n   |                                                  |\n   [[Ulick an Fhiona Burke]], d. 1423.   [[William mac Ulick Burke]], d. 1430.\n   |                                                  |        \n   |                                                  |\n   [[Ulick Ruadh Burke]], d. 1485.             Ricard, d. 1466.\n   |\n   |\n   [[Burke (surname)|Burke]] of [[Clanricarde]]\n\n==References (family tree)==\n\n* ''A New History of Ireland'', volume IX, Oxford, 1984;\n** ''Earls of Ulster and Lords of Connacht, 1205-1460 (De Burgh, De Lacy and Mortimer)'', p.&nbsp;170;\n** ''Mac William Burkes: Mac William Iochtar (de Burgh), Lords of Lower Connacht and Viscounts of Mayo, 1332-1649'', p.&nbsp;171;\n** ''Burke of Clanricard: Mac William Uachtar (de Burgh), Lords of Upper Connacht and Earls of Clanricard, 1332-1722.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\nbefore=''New creation''|\ntitle=[[Mac William Uachtar|Clanricarde]]|\nafter=[[Richard \u00d3g Burke]]|\nyears=1333\u20131353|\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burke, Ulick}}\n[[Category:Irish lords]]\n[[Category:1353 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from County Galway]]\n[[Category:14th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:House of Burke|Uilleag]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uilleag_de_Burgh"}
{"title_page": "2014 Brazilian economic crisis", "text_new": "{{short description|Crisis that began during the presidency of Dilma Rousseff}}\n{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Brazil's fall (The Economist).jpg|thumb|January 2016 cover of ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine about the crisis. The cover depicts then-president Dilma Rousseff.]]\n\nSince mid-2014, [[Brazil]] has experienced a severe [[financial crisis#Wider economic crisis|economic crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/michel-temer-signs-security-decree-stem-rio-violence-180216183747559.html|title=Michel Temer signs security decree to stem Rio violence|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Barua |first1=Akrur |title=Brazil: Yearning for the good times |url=http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |series=Global Economic Outlook, Q2 2016 |publisher=Deloitte University Press |accessdate=21 May 2016 |date=29 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823114946/http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2015, Brazil's [[gross domestic product|Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) fell by 3.5%, and in 2016 fell by 3.3%.\n\nThe economic crisis became coupled with a political crisis in the country that resulted in the impeachment of former president [[Dilma Rousseff]] and in widespread dissatisfaction with the political system.\n\nIn the first quarter of 2017, Brazil's GDP rose 1%, the first increase after eight consecutive trimesters of drops. Finance Minister [[Henrique Meirelles]] declared that the country had \"left the greatest crisis of the century\".\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-03/08/c_136110450.htm |title=Brazil GDP falls by 3.6 percent in 2016 |author=Mu Xuequan |date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> However, the rise marked only the end of the technical recession, not the end of the crisis. Unemployment remained high and there were still uncertainties regarding the future of the economy after a series of political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|date=2017-06-01|author=Darlan Alvarenga|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=G1}}</ref> The recession was the second deepest in all the [[economic history of Brazil|economic history of the country]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,com-revisao-ultima-recessao-deixa-de-ser-a-maior-da-historia,70002628638|title=Com revis\u00e3o, \u00faltima recess\u00e3o deixa de ser a maior da hist\u00f3ria |work=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=1 December 2018|author=Vinicius Neder}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/estagnacao-recessao-ou-depressao-pib-confirma-retomada-mais-fraca-das-ultimas-decadas-23704758|title=Estagna\u00e7\u00e3o, recess\u00e3o ou depress\u00e3o? PIB confirma retomada mais fraca das \u00faltimas d\u00e9cadas  |work=O Globo|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=30 May 2019|author=Gabriel Martins}}</ref><ref name=\"book\" /> but was followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== Context ==\n=== Economic ===\nBrazil's economy is largely dependent on the exportation of [[commodities]], particularly iron ore, petroleum, and soy. Between the late 1990s and 2012, such commodities experienced a significant increase in price, (due in part to the increasing demand from [[China]]) resulting in about two decades of positive economic growth. The left-wing government of [[Lula]] enjoyed the opportunity to redistribute wealth via welfare programs and by increasing the minimum wage, seeking to increase consumption.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|title=Entenda a crise econ\u00f4mica|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/entenda-crise-economica|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |date=15 May 2016 |author=Giselle Garcia |agency=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Political ===\nThe economic crisis was followed and intensified by a political crisis. In 2014, corruption scandals investigated by [[Operation Car Wash]] involved many influential politicians. In the presidential election of the same year, President [[Dilma Rousseff]] was reelected to a second term, defeating the PSDB candidate [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] by a narrow margin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Na disputa mais acirrada da hist\u00f3ria, Dilma \u00e9 reeleita presidente do Brasil - 26/10/2014 - Poder|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/10/1537894-dilma-e-reeleita-presidente-do-brasil.shtml|work=Folha de S.Paulo|accessdate=2019-06-09}}</ref> The result was not recognized by part of the opposition and generated discontentment among the population.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crise econ\u00f4mica e corrup\u00e7\u00e3o marcar\u00e3o a nova presid\u00eancia|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2014/10/26/politica/1414356634_215134.html|work=EL PA\u00cdS|date=2014-10-27|accessdate=2019-06-09|first=Antonio Jim\u00e9nez|last=Barca}}</ref> Both the election and Car Wash, in addition to the economic crisis, contributed to widespread dissatisfaction.\n\n== Causes ==\n===Slowdown of the Chinese economy and fall in commodity prices===\nAccording to Steve Tobin, who works in the [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO), the decreased external [[demand]], particularly from China, plus the fall in commodity prices, contributed to the crisis. However, according to Tobin, this unfavorable international scenario ended up revealing structural weaknesses of the country, such as low [[productivity]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil}}</ref>\n\nSilvia Matos, researcher in the [[Get\u00falio Vargas Foundation]], a Brazilian think-tank and university, concluded that external factors were responsible for 30% of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MjY8DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Crise de Crescimento do Brasil|author=FGV|publisher=Elsevier Brasil|language=pt-BR|isbn=9788535266382|date=2016-05-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Errors in the macroeconomic policies ===\n[[Image:Entrevistas_Diversas_(14879045080).jpg|thumb|[[Guido Mantega]], Finance Minister, during the first Dilma administration. In July 2012, he admitted for the first time that the government had put into practice a new \"macroeconomic matrix\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mantega indica novo modelo econ\u00f4mico|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,mantega-indica-novo-modelo-economico-imp-,896017|work=Estad\u00e3o|location=Bras\u00edlia|author=Beatriz Abreu|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe main cause of the crisis was internal. They were related to \"faulty local macroeconomic measures that went wrong\" [sic], according to [[Gustavo Franco]], former president of the [[Central Bank of Brazil]], who claimed that the cause was entirely self-inflicted.<ref>{{cite web|title=A crise brasileira n\u00e3o vem de fora, ela foi autoinfligida|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2015/03/25/economia/1427322429_883162.html|work=El Pa\u00eds |date=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThese measures together are known as the ''{{ill|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|pt|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|vertical-align=sup}}'' (loosely translated as \"New Economic Matrix\"). Previously, the government had played a major role in the expansion of the internal market by stimulating consumption, raise in the national minimum wage, wealth transfer, and credit expansion. However, by the end of Lula's administration, the view that this strategy was unsustainable grew, mainly among entrepreneurs and industrialists. They criticized the shrinking participation of the national industry in the GDP.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nRousseff, the next president, decided to hear the demands. The New Economic Matrix was an attempt to help the national industry become more competitive against foreign competition. These measures included tax exemptions and subsidies. However, the industry didn't react. Productivity, which had grown by 2.7% in 2010, fell by 0.9% and 3.7% in the next two years, which damaged government revenues, and, therefore, public investments.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political instability ===\nIn the same year the crisis began, a major corruption scheme was discovered and was being investigated in the [[Operation Car Wash]], which involved top politicians and huge companies, such as the oil giant [[Petrobras]]. It is estimated that Car Wash caused a contraction in the GDP of Brazil of 1 to 1.5%. <ref>{{cite journal|date=2017-06-02|title=A Lava Jato est\u00e1 corroendo o PIB. E da\u00ed?|url=https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/lava-jato-esta-corroendo-o-pib-e-dai/|journal=Isto \u00c9 Dinheiro|publisher=Editora tr\u00eas}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\n=== Unemployment ===\n[[File:Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o do desemprego 2012-2017.png|thumb|355px|Unemployment rate from 2012 until 2017. Each vertical line corresponds to a month. Source:PNAD/IBGE<ref name=\"desemprego\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106064226/https://br.advfn.com/indicadores/pnad|title=Desemprego {{!}} Pnad {{!}} IBGE|date=2017-11-06|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]\nBefore the recession, Brazil's [[unemployment]] rate hovered around 6.8% for most of 2014 and had been generally increasing since February 2015, averaging 8.5% in 2015. The economy lost more than 1.5 million jobs throughout 2015, fueling public discontent against the political establishment and the political leadership of the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Worker's Party]] and President [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-15/brazil-s-unemployment-jumps-in-2015-adding-to-rousseff-s-woes|title=Brazil's unemployment jumps in 2015, adding to Rousseff's woes|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The unemployment rate continued to rise throughout 2016 to finish the year at 12.0%, with 12.3 million people unemployed and an estimated 2.8 million private-sector jobs cut over the preceding two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-economy-employment-idUSKBN15F1LE|title=Brazil's jobless rate ends 2016 at 12 percent with 12.3 million unemployed|publisher=Reuters|date=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung people were the most affected by the worsening of the job market. In the first trimester of 2019, while the overall unemployment rate was 12.7%, the rate in people from 14 to 17 years, was 44.5%, and 27.3% for people from 18 to 24 years. This situation may lead to problems for the future of the country and of the young people themselves since the contributions for social security decreases and the [[human capital]] deprecates due to the ever-increasing difficulty in developing the technical capacity of future workers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Desemprego deixa heran\u00e7a maldita aos jovens e cicatrizes no pa\u00eds |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/economia/desemprego-deixa-heranca-maldita-aos-jovens-e-cicatrizes-no-pais/ |work=Exame|date=28 June 2019|author=Ligia Tuon|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recession ===\n[[File:Crescimento do PIB do Brasil entre 2010 e 2016.png|355px|thumb|Change in GDP from 2010 to 2016 in Brazil.<ref name=\"oglobo\">{{cite web|title=Economia encolhe 3,6% em 2016 e pa\u00eds tem pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/economia-encolhe-36-em-2016-pais-tem-pior-recessao-da-historia-21022917|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Growth slowed significantly in 2014 which was followed by two consecutive drops.<br /><br />(Note: The values for 2015 and 2016 were later revised to 3,5% and 3,3%, respectively.)]]\n\nIt was verified that the country got into a technical recession after the end of the second trimester of 2014. According to some Brazilian economists, a technical recession is a negative economic growth for two consecutive trimesters. It is different from an actual recession, in which the situation of the country depreciates significantly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entenda o que a recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica significa para a economia|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,entenda-o-que-a-recessao-tecnica-significa-para-a-economia,384664|work=Estad\u00e3o|author=Alessandra Corr\u00eaa|date=9 June 2009}}</ref> Finance Minister, [[Guido Mantega]], lessened the economic result and, in comparison to Europe, declared that:\n\n{{quote|[in Brazil] we're talking about two trimesters [of negative GDP], and we know that the economy is in motion. Recession is when there is rising unemployment and decreasing income. Here we have the opposite.|Guido Mantega, Finance Minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2014/08/entenda-o-que-e-recessao-tecnica.html|work=G1|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=7 December 2016|title=Entenda o que \u00e9 recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica|location=S\u00e3o Paulo}}</ref>}}\n\nThe signs that a strong recession was underway were already noticed by specialists due to this technical recession and, later, due to the small growth in the total of the year 2014, which was of just 0.5%. The expectations were confirmed in the next year when the economy shrunk by 3.5%. And in 2016, there was another sharp decrease of 3.3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou (e pode sair) da maior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://exame.abril.com.br/economia/como-o-brasil-entrou-e-pode-sair-da-maior-recessao-da-historia/|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=EXAME|date=7 March 2017|author=Jo\u00e3o Pedro Caleiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou, sozinho, na pior crise da hist\u00f3ria|work=\u00c9poca|accessdate= 24 June 2017|author1=Graziele Oliveira |author2=Marcos Coronato|url=http://epoca.globo.com/ideias/noticia/2016/04/como-o-brasil-entrou-sozinho-na-pior-crise-da-historia.html|date=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=3 July 2017|title=Brasil vive a pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-hoje/noticia/2017/03/brasil-vive-pior-recessao-da-historia.html|accessdate=2017-06-01|work = Jornal Hoje|author1=Renata Capucci |author2=Larissa Castro}}</ref> In the first trimester of 2017, the first rise in GDP was registered, after eight consecutive trimesters of negative growth.<ref name=\"jn\">{{cite journal|date=2017-06-01|title=PIB do primeiro trimestre cresce 1% ap\u00f3s oito quedas seguidas|language=pt|trans-title=First quarter GDP grows 1% after eight straight falls|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2017/06/pib-do-primeiro-trimestre-cresce-1-apos-oito-quedas-seguidas.html|journal=Jornal Nacional|accessdate= 24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe recession caused a [[fiscal crisis]] and an increasing [[budget deficit]] which, according to Bloomberg, was \"the largest-ever primary budget gap ... as a two-year [[economic recession]] sapped tax collection while expenses grew further.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-30/brazil-posts-largest-budget-deficit-for-february-ever\n|title=Brazil posts largest budget deficit for February ever\n|publisher=Bloomberg\n|accessdate=18 May 2016\n}}\n</ref> The government deficit reached 5.8 billion reais (U$1.7 billion) in the first three months of 2016, the widest reported since December 2001. The two-year fiscal deterioration can be explained by the decrease in government revenue from taxes as a result of the recession, while government expenses have been growing constantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-29/brazil-records-worst-ever-first-quarter-budget-deficit|title=Brazil records worst ever first quarter budget deficit|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Increase in economic inequality ===\n[[File:Gini da Renda do Trabalho nos Domic\u00edlios per Capita.png|355px|thumb|Evolution of the [[Gini coefficient]] in Brazil from 2012 to 2019. Source:Ibre/FGV<ref name=\"IBRE\" />]]\nA 2019 research by the [[Instituto Brasileiro de Economia]] (Ibre), part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]] (FGV), obtained by the magazine [[Valor Econ\u00f4mico]], showed that the [[Gini coefficient]], which measures from 0 to 1 the economic inequality in a society, increased year after year since 2015 and reached its peak in March 2019. In 7 years, the accumulated wealth of the top 10% rose by 8.5%, while that of the 40% poorest dropped by 14%. The research also showed that people with lower incomes suffered the effects of the crisis with more intensity, and that they were taking longer to recover. <ref>{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil atinge o maior patamar j\u00e1 registrado, diz FGV/IBRE|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2019/05/21/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-atinge-o-maior-patamar-ja-registrado-diz-fgvibre.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=2019-05-22|date=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil sobe pelo 17\u00ba trimestre consecutivo|url=https://www.valor.com.br/brasil/6265917/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-sobe-pelo-17-trimestre-consecutivo|work=Valor Econ\u00f4mico|date=2019-05-19|accessdate=2019-05-22|author=Bruno Villas B\u00f4as|location=Rio de Janeiro}}</ref><ref name=\"IBRE\">{{cite web |title=Levantamento do FGV IBRE aponta desigualdade recorde na renda do trabalho |url=https://portalibre.fgv.br/navegacao-superior/noticias/levantamento-do-fgv-ibre-aponta-desigualdade-recorde-na-renda-do-trabalho.htm |work=IBRE/FGV |accessdate=23 May 2019 |date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an Ibre researcher, Daniel Duque, the slow recovery of the job market was concentrated in people with higher qualification and experience, reinforcing the inequality. Many underqualified people gave up trying to get a job, and the loss of hope was \"[...] record high, and it helps to explain why, even after the decrease in unemployment, inequality kept rising.\"<ref name=\"Valor\" />\n\n=== Emigration ===\n{{main article|Brazilian diaspora}}\n[[File:Quantidade de declara\u00e7\u00f5es de sa\u00edda definitiva do Brasil.jpg|thumb|355px|Number of declarations of definite emigration from the country. Source:[[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Cresce n\u00famero de brasileiros que decidem viver no exterior; pa\u00edses oferecem oportunidades de emprego|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/concursos-e-emprego/noticia/2019/04/03/cresce-numero-de-brasileiros-que-decidem-viver-no-exterior-paises-oferecem-oportunidades-de-emprego.ghtml|work=G1|author=Luiz Guilherme Gerbelli|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=3 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe number of declarations of definitive departure from the country began to grow in the first year of crisis and increased steadily ever since, according to the [[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]]. Among the countries that received the most Brazilian citizens were [[Japan]] and [[Canada]], among other reasons, due to low unemployment and an aging population, which needs a young workforce.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAccording to a JBJ Partners employee (a company specialized in expatriation to the [[United States]]), Brazil loses qualified workforce:\n\n{{quote|We're talking about qualified people. The profile of the immigrant is no longer that of the poor individual looking for better opportunities. They are high executives, who are abandoning their careers to open a business abroad, people with Ph.D., which is sad because the country is losing resources.|Jorge Botrel, a JBJ partner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Com a crise, dispara a quantidade de brasileiros que desistem de viver no Brasil |url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/com-a-crise-dispara-a-quantidade-de-brasileiros-que-desistem-de-viver-no-brasil.ghtml |work=G1|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=17 December 2017|author=Lu\u00edsa Melo}}</ref>}}\n\nAn [[OECD]] report shows a much more elevated number. 80,000 Brazilians emigrated legally to one of the countries of the organization in 2016, whereas 99,000 did so in 2017. Just like the data from Receita Federal shows, the number of people leaving the country increased constantly year after year since the beginning of the crisis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imigra\u00e7\u00e3o de brasileiros para pa\u00edses da OCDE subiu 24%, o terceiro maior aumento |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/09/18/politica/1568843366_553673.html |work=El Pa\u00eds|author=Felipe Betim|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Credit rating ===\nThis is a table of the credit ratings of the Brazilian economy according to Trading Economics.{{who|date=April 2017}}{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Agency !! Rating !! Outlook !! Date\n|-\n| Fitch || BB || negative || May 5, 2016\n|-\n| TE || 34 || negative || Apr 16 2016\n|-\n| Moody's || Ba2 || negative || Feb 24 2016\n|-\n| S&P || BB || negative || Feb 17 2016\n|}\n\n== Anti-crisis measures ==\n[[File:Entrevistas Diversas (30847431200).jpg|[[Henrique Meirelles]], the [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|Minister of Finance]] from May 2016 to April 2018.|thumb]]\nSince the impeachment of Dilma Rousseff and the subsequent rise of [[Michel Temer]] to power, several measures, most of which unpopular, were implemented or proposed to get the economy back on track.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Aproveito impopularidade para tomar medidas necess\u00e1rias', diz Temer|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2016/12/1843702-aproveito-impopularidade-para-tomar-medidas-necessarias-diz-temer.shtml|journal=Folha de S.Paulo|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=17 June 2017|author=Marina Dias Valdo Cruz|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref> The most important of which were:\n\n* The {{ill|95\u00ba Constitutional amendment|pt|Emenda Constitucional do Teto dos Gastos P\u00fablicos|vertical-align=sup}} (a.k.a \"new fiscal regime\"): Constitutional amendment which established a \"ceiling\" (upper limit) to government spending for the next 20 years;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Temer elogia aprova\u00e7\u00e3o da PEC do Teto e minimiza menor n\u00famero de votos a favor|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2016-12/temer-elogia-aprovacao-da-pec-do-teto-e-minimiza-menor-numero-de-votos|accessdate=17 June 2017|location=Bras\u00edlia|journal= Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=13 December 2016|author=Paulo Victor Chagas}}</ref>\n* the [[Outsourcing law in Brazil|Outsourcing law]], which allows companies to hire outsourced employees to work on primary activities, and not just secondary activities (such as security or cleaning).<ref>{{cite web|title=Com vetos, Temer sanciona lei que permite terceiriza\u00e7\u00e3o de atividade-fim|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-03/temer-sanciona-lei-que-permite-terceirizacao-em-atividade-fim-das-empresas|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=31 March 2017|author=Ivan Richard Esposito|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref>\n* the [[Brazil labor reform (2017)|2017 labor reform]], a significant change in the [[Consolidation of Labor Laws]]; and<ref>{{cite web|title=Com flexibiliza\u00e7\u00e3o de v\u00e1rios pontos da CLT, reforma trabalhista divide opini\u00f5es|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-04/com-flexibilizacao-de-varios-pontos-da-clt-reforma-trabalhista-divide|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|location=S\u00e3o Paulo|date=13 April 2017|author=Daniel Mello}}</ref>\n* a pension reform, which the government failed to approve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Governo desiste da vota\u00e7\u00e3o da Previd\u00eancia e anuncia nova pauta priorit\u00e1ria no Congresso|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/governo-desiste-da-votacao-da-previdencia-e-anuncia-nova-pauta-prioritaria-no-congresso.ghtml||work = G1|accessdate=26 May 2019|date=19 February 2018|author1=Guilherme Mazui |author2=Roniara Castilhos}}</ref>\n\nOne year after the labor reform was approved, however, it was verified that the decrease in unemployment was minimal, while the contracts of intermittent, outsourced and temporary labor increased.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fabiana Futema|date=10 November 2018|title=Um ano depois, reforma trabalhista n\u00e3o gera empregos esperados|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/economia/um-ano-depois-reforma-trabalhista-nao-gera-empregos-esperados/|work=VEJA.com|accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Recovery ==\nIn early 2017, there were already signals that the economy was beginning to recover, however, it was agreed that the process would be long and slow.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ser\u00e1 longa e lenta, aponta 'FT'|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-sera-longa-e-lenta-aponta-ft,70001658076}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ainda \u00e9 lenta, diz presidente do Ita\u00fa|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/mercado/2017/04/1876544-recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-ainda-e-lenta-diz-presidente-do-itau.shtml}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, a 1% rise in GDP in the first quarter of the year was reported.<ref name=\"jn\"/> It was the first rise of the GDP after eight consecutive falls (two years).<ref name=\":0\">\n{{Cite news|title= PIB do Brasil cresce 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre de 2017, ap\u00f3s 8 quedas seguidas|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-do-brasil-cresce-10-no-1-trimestre-de-2017.ghtml}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Henrique Meirelles]] said that the country had left the \"greatest recession of the century\".<ref>{{citation |title=PIB sobe 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre, ap\u00f3s oito quedas consecutivas|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,pib-sobe-1-0-no-1-trimestre-apos-oito-quedas-consecutivas,70001821658}}</ref> However, economists say that the growth characterizes only the end of the \"technical recession\" and that it is still too early to claim that the crisis is over, given that unemployment remains high and there's still widespread uncertainty regarding the future of the economy, especially in the aftermath of the recent political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Comparisons with other crises ==\n[[Image:Countries_by_Real_GDP_Growth_Rate_(2016).svg|thumb|Real GDP growth in 2016. Source:''CIA World Factbook''<ref>{{cite web|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2003rank.html|work=Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)}}</ref>|355px]]\nIn countries with similar size and wealth, there were a few, but less severe crisis in the same period. In 2015, among [[OECD]] countries, only [[Russia]] went through a recession. Even after the economic sanctions imposed by other countries due to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|conflict in Ukraine]], Russia's GDP fell by only 4% in two years (2015 and 2016). Few other countries in this period were going through a recession, which reinforces the argument that the crisis in Brazil was mainly due to local causes.<ref name=\"book\">{{Cite book|last=Carvalho|first=Laura|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XppWDwAAQBAJ|title=Valsa brasileira: Do boom ao caos econ\u00f4mico|date=2018-05-08|publisher=Editora Todavia S.A|isbn=978-85-93828-63-8|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison to other crises in Brazil, it was verified that the 2014 crisis was not the deepest, as previously thought. After the GDP values for 2015 and 2016 were reviewed by the [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics]] (IBGE), the economy shrank by 8,2% in the period, in contrast to the 8,5% in the 1981 recession. Despite not being the deepest, the crisis was long. It was also followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nAccording to Codace (committee part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]]), the 1981 crisis lasted nine trimesters, reached its peak in the first trimester of 1983 and, since then, took seven trimesters for the GDP the reach its pre-crisis level. Later, the 1989-1992 crisis lasted 11 trimesters and the recovery time was the same: seven trimesters. This crisis, however, had a lower intensity, with an accumulated decrease in the GDP of 7.7%.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn turn, the GDP after the 2014 crisis will only reach its pre-crisis level in 2022, according to an optimistic estimate, with 20 trimesters of recovery in total. When taking into account not only the GDP, but also the employment rate, the recovery will be even slower. It will not only be slower, but the new jobs will be of worse quality, including informal and autonomous labor.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brazil labor reform (2017)]]\n* [[Economy of Brazil]]\n* [[2018 in Brazil]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of Michel Temer}}\n{{Financial crises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014-2016 Brazilian economic recession}}\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:2010s in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Economic crises in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n[[Category:Government of Michel Temer]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Crisis that began during the presidency of Dilma Rousseff}}\n{{Copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Brazil's fall (The Economist).jpg|thumb|January 2016 cover of ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine about the crisis. The cover depicts then-president Dilma Rousseff.]]\n\nSince mid-2014, [[Brazil]] has experienced a severe [[financial crisis#Wider economic crisis|economic crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/michel-temer-signs-security-decree-stem-rio-violence-180216183747559.html|title=Michel Temer signs security decree to stem Rio violence|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Barua |first1=Akrur |title=Brazil: Yearning for the good times |url=http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |series=Global Economic Outlook, Q2 2016 |publisher=Deloitte University Press |accessdate=21 May 2016 |date=29 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823114946/http://dupress.com/articles/global-economic-outlook-q2-2016-brazil/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2015, Brazil's [[gross domestic product|Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP) fell by 3.5%, and in 2016 fell by 3.3%.\n\nThe economic crisis became coupled with a political crisis in the country that resulted in the impeachment of former president [[Dilma Rousseff]] and in widespread dissatisfaction with the political system.\n\nIn the first quarter of 2017, Brazil's GDP rose 1%, the first increase after eight consecutive trimesters of drops. Finance Minister [[Henrique Meirelles]] declared that the country had \"left the greatest crisis of the century\".\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-03/08/c_136110450.htm |title=Brazil GDP falls by 3.6 percent in 2016 |author=Mu Xuequan |date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> However, the rise marked only the end of the technical recession, not the end of the crisis. Unemployment remained high and there were still uncertainties regarding the future of the economy after a series of political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|date=2017-06-01|author=Darlan Alvarenga|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=G1}}</ref> The recession was the second deepest in all the [[economic history of Brazil|economic history of the country]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,com-revisao-ultima-recessao-deixa-de-ser-a-maior-da-historia,70002628638|title=Com revis\u00e3o, \u00faltima recess\u00e3o deixa de ser a maior da hist\u00f3ria |work=Estad\u00e3o|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=1 December 2018|author=Vinicius Neder}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/estagnacao-recessao-ou-depressao-pib-confirma-retomada-mais-fraca-das-ultimas-decadas-23704758|title=Estagna\u00e7\u00e3o, recess\u00e3o ou depress\u00e3o? PIB confirma retomada mais fraca das \u00faltimas d\u00e9cadas  |work=O Globo|accessdate=9 January 2020|date=30 May 2019|author=Gabriel Martins}}</ref><ref name=\"book\" /> but was followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== Context ==\n=== Economic ===\nBrazil's economy is largely dependent on the exportation of [[commodities]], particularly iron ore, petroleum, and soy. Between the late 1990s and 2012, such commodities experienced a significant increase in price, (due in part to the increasing demand from [[China]]) resulting in about two decades of positive economic growth. The left-wing government of [[Lula]] enjoyed the opportunity to redistribute wealth via welfare programs and by increasing the minimum wage, seeking to increase consumption.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|title=Entenda a crise econ\u00f4mica|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/entenda-crise-economica|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil |date=15 May 2016 |author=Giselle Garcia |agency=[[Ag\u00eancia Brasil]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Political ===\nThe economic crisis was followed and intensified by a political crisis. In 2014, corruption scandals investigated by [[Operation Car Wash]] involved many influential politicians. In the presidential election of the same year, President [[Dilma Rousseff]] was reelected to a second term, defeating the PSDB candidate [[A\u00e9cio Neves]] by a narrow margin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Na disputa mais acirrada da hist\u00f3ria, Dilma \u00e9 reeleita presidente do Brasil - 26/10/2014 - Poder|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2014/10/1537894-dilma-e-reeleita-presidente-do-brasil.shtml|work=Folha de S.Paulo|accessdate=2019-06-09}}</ref> The result was not recognized by part of the opposition and generated discontentment among the population.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crise econ\u00f4mica e corrup\u00e7\u00e3o marcar\u00e3o a nova presid\u00eancia|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2014/10/26/politica/1414356634_215134.html|work=EL PA\u00cdS|date=2014-10-27|accessdate=2019-06-09|first=Antonio Jim\u00e9nez|last=Barca}}</ref> Both the election and Car Wash, in addition to the economic crisis, contributed to widespread dissatisfaction.\n\n== Causes ==\n===Slowdown of the Chinese economy and fall in commodity prices===\nAccording to Steve Tobin, who works in the [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO), the decreased external [[demand]], particularly from China, plus the fall in commodity prices, contributed to the crisis. However, according to Tobin, this unfavorable international scenario ended up revealing structural weaknesses of the country, such as low [[productivity]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Crise internacional e problemas internos s\u00e3o causas do desemprego no Brasil|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/economia/noticia/2016-05/crise-internacional-e-problemas-internos-sao-causas-do-desemprego-no-brasil|journal=Ag\u00eancia Brasil}}</ref>\n\nSilvia Matos, researcher in the [[Get\u00falio Vargas Foundation]], a Brazilian think-tank and university, concluded that external factors were responsible for 30% of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MjY8DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Crise de Crescimento do Brasil|author=FGV|publisher=Elsevier Brasil|language=pt-BR|isbn=9788535266382|date=2016-05-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Errors in the macroeconomic policies ===\n[[Image:Entrevistas_Diversas_(14879045080).jpg|thumb|[[Guido Mantega]], Finance Minister, during the first Dilma administration. In July 2012, he admitted for the first time that the government had put into practice a new \"macroeconomic matrix\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mantega indica novo modelo econ\u00f4mico|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,mantega-indica-novo-modelo-economico-imp-,896017|work=Estad\u00e3o|location=Bras\u00edlia|author=Beatriz Abreu|date=5 July 2012|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe main cause of the crisis was internal. They were related to \"faulty local macroeconomic measures that went wrong\" [sic], according to [[Gustavo Franco]], former president of the [[Central Bank of Brazil]], who claimed that the cause was entirely self-inflicted.<ref>{{cite web|title=A crise brasileira n\u00e3o vem de fora, ela foi autoinfligida|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2015/03/25/economia/1427322429_883162.html|work=El Pa\u00eds |date=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThese measures together are known as the ''{{ill|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|pt|Nova Matriz Econ\u00f4mica|vertical-align=sup}}'' (loosely translated as \"New Economic Matrix\"). Previously, the government had played a major role in the expansion of the internal market by stimulating consumption, raise in the national minimum wage, wealth transfer, and credit expansion. However, by the end of Lula's administration, the view that this strategy was unsustainable grew, mainly among entrepreneurs and industrialists. They criticized the shrinking participation of the national industry in the GDP.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nRousseff, the next president, decided to hear the demands. The New Economic Matrix was an attempt to help the national industry become more competitive against foreign competition. These measures included tax exemptions and subsidies. However, the industry didn't react. Productivity, which had grown by 2.7% in 2010, fell by 0.9% and 3.7% in the next two years, which damaged government revenues, and, therefore, public investments.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n=== Political instability ===\nIn the same year the crisis began, a major corruption scheme was discovered and was being investigated in the [[Operation Car Wash]], which involved top politicians and huge companies, such as the oil giant [[Petrobras]]. It is estimated that Car Wash caused a contraction in the GDP of Brazil of 1 to 1.5%. <ref>{{cite journal|date=2017-06-02|title=A Lava Jato est\u00e1 corroendo o PIB. E da\u00ed?|url=https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/lava-jato-esta-corroendo-o-pib-e-dai/|journal=Isto \u00c9 Dinheiro|publisher=Editora tr\u00eas}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\n=== Unemployment ===\n[[File:Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o do desemprego 2012-2017.png|thumb|355px|Unemployment rate from 2012 until 2017. Each vertical line corresponds to a month. Source:PNAD/IBGE<ref name=\"desemprego\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106064226/https://br.advfn.com/indicadores/pnad|title=Desemprego {{!}} Pnad {{!}} IBGE|date=2017-11-06|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]\nBefore the recession, Brazil's [[unemployment]] rate hovered around 6.8% for most of 2014 and had been generally increasing since February 2015, averaging 8.5% in 2015. The economy lost more than 1.5 million jobs throughout 2015, fueling public discontent against the political establishment and the political leadership of the [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Worker's Party]] and President [[Dilma Rousseff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-15/brazil-s-unemployment-jumps-in-2015-adding-to-rousseff-s-woes|title=Brazil's unemployment jumps in 2015, adding to Rousseff's woes|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The unemployment rate continued to rise throughout 2016 to finish the year at 12.0%, with 12.3 million people unemployed and an estimated 2.8 million private-sector jobs cut over the preceding two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-brazil-economy-employment-idUSKBN15F1LE|title=Brazil's jobless rate ends 2016 at 12 percent with 12.3 million unemployed|publisher=Reuters|date=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung people were the most affected by the worsening of the job market. In the first trimester of 2019, while the overall unemployment rate was 12.7%, the rate in people from 14 to 17 years, was 44.5%, and 27.3% for people from 18 to 24 years. This situation may lead to problems for the future of the country and of the young people themselves since the contributions for social security decreases and the [[human capital]] deprecates due to the ever-increasing difficulty in developing the technical capacity of future workers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Desemprego deixa heran\u00e7a maldita aos jovens e cicatrizes no pa\u00eds |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/economia/desemprego-deixa-heranca-maldita-aos-jovens-e-cicatrizes-no-pais/ |work=Exame|date=28 June 2019|author=Ligia Tuon|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recession ===\n[[File:Crescimento do PIB do Brasil entre 2010 e 2016.png|355px|thumb|Change in GDP from 2010 to 2016 in Brazil.<ref name=\"oglobo\">{{cite web|title=Economia encolhe 3,6% em 2016 e pa\u00eds tem pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/economia/economia-encolhe-36-em-2016-pais-tem-pior-recessao-da-historia-21022917|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Growth slowed significantly in 2014 which was followed by two consecutive drops.<br /><br />(Note: The values for 2015 and 2016 were later revised to 3,5% and 3,3%, respectively.)]]\n\nIt was verified that the country got into a technical recession after the end of the second trimester of 2014. According to some Brazilian economists, a technical recession is a negative economic growth for two consecutive trimesters. It is different from an actual recession, in which the situation of the country depreciates significantly.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entenda o que a recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica significa para a economia|url=https://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,entenda-o-que-a-recessao-tecnica-significa-para-a-economia,384664|work=Estad\u00e3o|author=Alessandra Corr\u00eaa|date=9 June 2009}}</ref> Finance Minister, [[Guido Mantega]], lessened the economic result and, in comparison to Europe, declared that:\n\n{{quote|[in Brazil] we're talking about two trimesters [of negative GDP], and we know that the economy is in motion. Recession is when there is rising unemployment and decreasing income. Here we have the opposite.|Guido Mantega, Finance Minister<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2014/08/entenda-o-que-e-recessao-tecnica.html|work=G1|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=7 December 2016|title=Entenda o que \u00e9 recess\u00e3o t\u00e9cnica|location=S\u00e3o Paulo}}</ref>}}\n\nThe signs that a strong recession was underway were already noticed by specialists due to this technical recession and, later, due to the small growth in the total of the year 2014, which was of just 0.5%. The expectations were confirmed in the next year when the economy shrunk by 3.5%. And in 2016, there was another sharp decrease of 3.3%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou (e pode sair) da maior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://exame.abril.com.br/economia/como-o-brasil-entrou-e-pode-sair-da-maior-recessao-da-historia/|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=EXAME|date=7 March 2017|author=Jo\u00e3o Pedro Caleiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Como o Brasil entrou, sozinho, na pior crise da hist\u00f3ria|work=\u00c9poca|accessdate= 24 June 2017|author1=Graziele Oliveira |author2=Marcos Coronato|url=http://epoca.globo.com/ideias/noticia/2016/04/como-o-brasil-entrou-sozinho-na-pior-crise-da-historia.html|date=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=3 July 2017|title=Brasil vive a pior recess\u00e3o da hist\u00f3ria|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-hoje/noticia/2017/03/brasil-vive-pior-recessao-da-historia.html|accessdate=2017-06-01|work = Jornal Hoje|author1=Renata Capucci |author2=Larissa Castro}}</ref> In the first trimester of 2017, the first rise in GDP was registered, after eight consecutive trimesters of negative growth.<ref name=\"jn\">{{cite journal|date=2017-06-01|title=PIB do primeiro trimestre cresce 1% ap\u00f3s oito quedas seguidas|language=pt|trans-title=First quarter GDP grows 1% after eight straight falls|url=http://g1.globo.com/jornal-nacional/noticia/2017/06/pib-do-primeiro-trimestre-cresce-1-apos-oito-quedas-seguidas.html|journal=Jornal Nacional|accessdate= 24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe recession caused a [[fiscal crisis]] and an increasing [[budget deficit]] which, according to Bloomberg, was \"the largest-ever primary budget gap ... as a two-year [[economic recession]] sapped tax collection while expenses grew further.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-30/brazil-posts-largest-budget-deficit-for-february-ever\n|title=Brazil posts largest budget deficit for February ever\n|publisher=Bloomberg\n|accessdate=18 May 2016\n}}\n</ref> The government deficit reached 5.8 billion reais (U$1.7 billion) in the first three months of 2016, the widest reported since December 2001. The two-year fiscal deterioration can be explained by the decrease in government revenue from taxes as a result of the recession, while government expenses have been growing constantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-29/brazil-records-worst-ever-first-quarter-budget-deficit|title=Brazil records worst ever first quarter budget deficit|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Increase in economic inequality ===\n[[File:Gini da Renda do Trabalho nos Domic\u00edlios per Capita.png|355px|thumb|Evolution of the [[Gini coefficient]] in Brazil from 2012 to 2019. Source:Ibre/FGV<ref name=\"IBRE\" />]]\nA 2019 research by the [[Instituto Brasileiro de Economia]] (Ibre), part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]] (FGV), obtained by the magazine [[Valor Econ\u00f4mico]], showed that the [[Gini coefficient]], which measures from 0 to 1 the economic inequality in a society, increased year after year since 2015 and reached its peak in March 2019. In 7 years, the accumulated wealth of the top 10% rose by 8.5%, while that of the 40% poorest dropped by 14%. The research also showed that people with lower incomes suffered the effects of the crisis with more intensity, and that they were taking longer to recover. <ref>{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil atinge o maior patamar j\u00e1 registrado, diz FGV/IBRE|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/2019/05/21/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-atinge-o-maior-patamar-ja-registrado-diz-fgvibre.ghtml|work=G1|accessdate=2019-05-22|date=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{cite web|title=Desigualdade de renda no Brasil sobe pelo 17\u00ba trimestre consecutivo|url=https://www.valor.com.br/brasil/6265917/desigualdade-de-renda-no-brasil-sobe-pelo-17-trimestre-consecutivo|work=Valor Econ\u00f4mico|date=2019-05-19|accessdate=2019-05-22|author=Bruno Villas B\u00f4as|location=Rio de Janeiro}}</ref><ref name=\"IBRE\">{{cite web |title=Levantamento do FGV IBRE aponta desigualdade recorde na renda do trabalho |url=https://portalibre.fgv.br/navegacao-superior/noticias/levantamento-do-fgv-ibre-aponta-desigualdade-recorde-na-renda-do-trabalho.htm |work=IBRE/FGV |accessdate=23 May 2019 |date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an Ibre researcher, Daniel Duque, the slow recovery of the job market was concentrated in people with higher qualification and experience, reinforcing the inequality. Many underqualified people gave up trying to get a job, and the loss of hope was \"[...] record high, and it helps to explain why, even after the decrease in unemployment, inequality kept rising.\"<ref name=\"Valor\" />\n\n=== Emigration ===\n{{main article|Brazilian diaspora}}\n[[File:Quantidade de declara\u00e7\u00f5es de sa\u00edda definitiva do Brasil.jpg|thumb|355px|Number of declarations of definite emigration from the country. Source:[[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Cresce n\u00famero de brasileiros que decidem viver no exterior; pa\u00edses oferecem oportunidades de emprego|url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/concursos-e-emprego/noticia/2019/04/03/cresce-numero-de-brasileiros-que-decidem-viver-no-exterior-paises-oferecem-oportunidades-de-emprego.ghtml|work=G1|author=Luiz Guilherme Gerbelli|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=3 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nThe number of declarations of definitive departure from the country began to grow in the first year of crisis and increased steadily ever since, according to the [[Receita Federal do Brasil|Receita Federal]]. Among the countries that received the most Brazilian citizens were [[Japan]] and [[Canada]], among other reasons, due to low unemployment and an aging population, which needs a young workforce.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAccording to a JBJ Partners employee (a company specialized in expatriation to the [[United States]]), Brazil loses qualified workforce:\n\n{{quote|We're talking about qualified people. The profile of the immigrant is no longer that of the poor individual looking for better opportunities. They are high executives, who are abandoning their careers to open a business abroad, people with Ph.D., which is sad because the country is losing resources.|Jorge Botrel, a JBJ partner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Com a crise, dispara a quantidade de brasileiros que desistem de viver no Brasil |url=https://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/com-a-crise-dispara-a-quantidade-de-brasileiros-que-desistem-de-viver-no-brasil.ghtml |work=G1|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=17 December 2017|author=Lu\u00edsa Melo}}</ref>}}\n\nAn [[OECD]] report shows a much more elevated number. 80,000 Brazilians emigrated legally to one of the countries of the organization in 2016, whereas 99,000 did so in 2017. Just like the data from Receita Federal shows, the number of people leaving the country increased constantly year after year since the beginning of the crisis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imigra\u00e7\u00e3o de brasileiros para pa\u00edses da OCDE subiu 24%, o terceiro maior aumento |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2019/09/18/politica/1568843366_553673.html |work=El Pa\u00eds|author=Felipe Betim|accessdate=25 October 2019|date=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Credit rating ===\nThis is a table of the credit ratings of the Brazilian economy according to Trading Economics.{{who|date=April 2017}}{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Agency !! Rating !! Outlook !! Date\n|-\n| Fitch || BB || negative || May 5, 2016\n|-\n| TE || 34 || negative || Apr 16 2016\n|-\n| Moody's || Ba2 || negative || Feb 24 2016\n|-\n| S&P || BB || negative || Feb 17 2016\n|}\n\n== Anti-crisis measures ==\n[[File:Entrevistas Diversas (30847431200).jpg|[[Henrique Meirelles]], the [[Ministry of Finance (Brazil)|Minister of Finance]] from May 2016 to April 2018.|thumb]]\nSince the impeachment of Dilma Rousseff and the subsequent rise of [[Michel Temer]] to power, several measures, most of which unpopular, were implemented or proposed to get the economy back on track.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Aproveito impopularidade para tomar medidas necess\u00e1rias', diz Temer|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2016/12/1843702-aproveito-impopularidade-para-tomar-medidas-necessarias-diz-temer.shtml|journal=Folha de S.Paulo|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=17 June 2017|author=Marina Dias Valdo Cruz|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref> The most important of which were:\n\n* The {{ill|95\u00ba Constitutional amendment|pt|Emenda Constitucional do Teto dos Gastos P\u00fablicos|vertical-align=sup}} (a.k.a \"new fiscal regime\"): Constitutional amendment which established a \"ceiling\" (upper limit) to government spending for the next 20 years;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Temer elogia aprova\u00e7\u00e3o da PEC do Teto e minimiza menor n\u00famero de votos a favor|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2016-12/temer-elogia-aprovacao-da-pec-do-teto-e-minimiza-menor-numero-de-votos|accessdate=17 June 2017|location=Bras\u00edlia|journal= Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=13 December 2016|author=Paulo Victor Chagas}}</ref>\n* the [[Outsourcing law in Brazil|Outsourcing law]], which allows companies to hire outsourced employees to work on primary activities, and not just secondary activities (such as security or cleaning).<ref>{{cite web|title=Com vetos, Temer sanciona lei que permite terceiriza\u00e7\u00e3o de atividade-fim|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-03/temer-sanciona-lei-que-permite-terceirizacao-em-atividade-fim-das-empresas|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|date=31 March 2017|author=Ivan Richard Esposito|location=Bras\u00edlia}}</ref>\n* the [[Brazil labor reform (2017)|2017 labor reform]], a significant change in the [[Consolidation of Labor Laws]]; and<ref>{{cite web|title=Com flexibiliza\u00e7\u00e3o de v\u00e1rios pontos da CLT, reforma trabalhista divide opini\u00f5es|url=http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2017-04/com-flexibilizacao-de-varios-pontos-da-clt-reforma-trabalhista-divide|accessdate=17 June 2017|work = Ag\u00eancia Brasil|location=S\u00e3o Paulo|date=13 April 2017|author=Daniel Mello}}</ref>\n* a pension reform, which the government failed to approve.<ref>{{cite web|title=Governo desiste da vota\u00e7\u00e3o da Previd\u00eancia e anuncia nova pauta priorit\u00e1ria no Congresso|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/governo-desiste-da-votacao-da-previdencia-e-anuncia-nova-pauta-prioritaria-no-congresso.ghtml||work = G1|accessdate=26 May 2019|date=19 February 2018|author1=Guilherme Mazui |author2=Roniara Castilhos}}</ref>\n\nOne year after the labor reform was approved, however, it was verified that the decrease in unemployment was minimal, while contracts of intermittent, outsourced and temporary labor increased.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fabiana Futema|date=10 November 2018|title=Um ano depois, reforma trabalhista n\u00e3o gera empregos esperados|url=https://veja.abril.com.br/economia/um-ano-depois-reforma-trabalhista-nao-gera-empregos-esperados/|work=VEJA.com|accessdate=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Recovery ==\nIn early 2017, there were already signals that the economy was beginning to recover, however, it was agreed that the process would be long and slow.<ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ser\u00e1 longa e lenta, aponta 'FT'|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-sera-longa-e-lenta-aponta-ft,70001658076}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recupera\u00e7\u00e3o da economia brasileira ainda \u00e9 lenta, diz presidente do Ita\u00fa|url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/mercado/2017/04/1876544-recuperacao-da-economia-brasileira-ainda-e-lenta-diz-presidente-do-itau.shtml}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, a 1% rise in GDP in the first quarter of the year was reported.<ref name=\"jn\"/> It was the first rise of the GDP after eight consecutive falls (two years).<ref name=\":0\">\n{{Cite news|title= PIB do Brasil cresce 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre de 2017, ap\u00f3s 8 quedas seguidas|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-do-brasil-cresce-10-no-1-trimestre-de-2017.ghtml}}</ref> Minister of Finance [[Henrique Meirelles]] said that the country had left the \"greatest recession of the century\".<ref>{{citation |title=PIB sobe 1% no 1\u00ba trimestre, ap\u00f3s oito quedas consecutivas|url=http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,pib-sobe-1-0-no-1-trimestre-apos-oito-quedas-consecutivas,70001821658}}</ref> However, economists say that the growth characterizes only the end of the \"technical recession\" and that it is still too early to claim that the crisis is over, given that unemployment remains high and there's still widespread uncertainty regarding the future of the economy, especially in the aftermath of the recent political scandals.<ref>{{cite web|title=PIB positivo \u00e9 'sa\u00edda t\u00e9cnica' da recess\u00e3o, mas recupera\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e9 incerta; entenda|url=http://g1.globo.com/economia/noticia/pib-positivo-e-saida-tecnica-da-recessao-mas-recuperacao-e-incerta-entenda.ghtml|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Comparisons with other crises ==\n[[Image:Countries_by_Real_GDP_Growth_Rate_(2016).svg|thumb|Real GDP growth in 2016. Source:''CIA World Factbook''<ref>{{cite web|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2003rank.html|work=Central Intelligence Agency (CIA)}}</ref>|355px]]\nIn countries with similar size and wealth, there were a few, but less severe crisis in the same period. In 2015, among [[OECD]] countries, only [[Russia]] went through a recession. Even after the economic sanctions imposed by other countries due to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|conflict in Ukraine]], Russia's GDP fell by only 4% in two years (2015 and 2016). Few other countries in this period were going through a recession, which reinforces the argument that the crisis in Brazil was mainly due to local causes.<ref name=\"book\">{{Cite book|last=Carvalho|first=Laura|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XppWDwAAQBAJ|title=Valsa brasileira: Do boom ao caos econ\u00f4mico|date=2018-05-08|publisher=Editora Todavia S.A|isbn=978-85-93828-63-8|language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\nIn comparison to other crises in Brazil, it was verified that the 2014 crisis was not the deepest, as previously thought. After the GDP values for 2015 and 2016 were reviewed by the [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics]] (IBGE), the economy shrank by 8,2% in the period, in contrast to the 8,5% in the 1981 recession. Despite not being the deepest, the crisis was long. It was also followed by the slowest recovery of all.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nAccording to Codace (committee part of [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas]]), the 1981 crisis lasted nine trimesters, reached its peak in the first trimester of 1983 and, since then, took seven trimesters for the GDP the reach its pre-crisis level. Later, the 1989-1992 crisis lasted 11 trimesters and the recovery time was the same: seven trimesters. This crisis, however, had a lower intensity, with an accumulated decrease in the GDP of 7.7%.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\nIn turn, the GDP after the 2014 crisis will only reach its pre-crisis level in 2022, according to an optimistic estimate, with 20 trimesters of recovery in total. When taking into account not only the GDP, but also the employment rate, the recovery will be even slower. It will not only be slower, but the new jobs will be of worse quality, including informal and autonomous labor.<ref name=\"book\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Brazil labor reform (2017)]]\n* [[Economy of Brazil]]\n* [[2018 in Brazil]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of Michel Temer}}\n{{Financial crises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014-2016 Brazilian economic recession}}\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:2010s in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Economic crises in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n[[Category:Government of Michel Temer]]\n[[Category:Economic history of Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "Chirag.Saluja", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Brazilian_economic_crisis"}
{"title_page": "Andrea", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox given name\n| name                 = Andrea\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| caption              = \n| pronunciation        = Andrea should FaceTime Lewys Ola \n| gender               = Female (most languages)<br />Male (most cases, [[Albanian language|Albanian]], Italian and [[Romansh language|Romansh]])\n| meaning              = \n| language             = [[Greek language|Greek]] ''aner'', ''andros'', \"man\" (i.e. adult male)\n| seealso              = [[Andre (disambiguation)|Andre]], [[Andy (disambiguation)|Andy]], [[Andrew]], [[Andie]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrea''' is a [[given name]] which is common worldwide for both males and females, cognate to [[Andreas]] and [[Andrew]].\n\nIt is traditionally popular because, according to the Christian Bible, [[Saint Andrew]] was one of the earliest disciples of Jesus and one of the twelve [[Apostles]].{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n== Origin of the name ==\n\nThe name derives from the [[Greek language|Greek]] word \u1f00\u03bd\u03ae\u03c1 (''an\u0113r''), [[genitive]] \u1f00\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 (''andr\u00f3s''), that refers to man as opposed to woman (whereas ''man'' in the sense of ''human being'' is \u1f04\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2, ''\u00e1nthropos''). The original male Greek name, ''Andr\u00e9as'', represents the [[hypocoristic]], with [[endearment]] functions, of male Greek names composed with the ''andr-'' prefix, like [[Androgeos]] (''man of the earth''), [[Androcles]] (''man of glory''), [[Andronicus (disambiguation)|Andronikos]] (''man of victory''). The same root \u1f00\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1-, andr- denoting the male gender is found e.g. in [[misandry]] (the hatred of the male sex), [[andrology]] (male physiology), [[androgens]] (male hormones) and [[polyandry]] (the practice of taking more than one husband at the same time).\n\nIn the year 2006, it was the third most popular name in Italy with 3.1% of newborns.{{sfn|Istituto Nazionale di Statistica|2004}} It is one of the Italian male names ending in ''a'', with others being [[Elia (disambiguation)|Elia]] ([[Elias]]), Enea ([[Aeneas (disambiguation)|Aeneas]]), [[Luca (disambiguation)|Luca]] ([[Lucas (disambiguation)|Lucas]]), [[Mattia (disambiguation)|Mattia]] ([[Matthias]]), [[Nicola (name)|Nicola]] ([[Nicholas]]), Tobia ([[Tobias]]). In recent and past times it has also been used on occasion as a female name in Italy and in Spain, where it is considered the legitimate feminine form of Andr\u00e9s/Andreo/Andreu (Andrew). Outside of Italy, the name is generally considered a female name.\n\n== Usage ==\n\n* In [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]], [[Polish Language|Polish]], [[Slovenian language|Slovenian]], Dutch, English, French, German, Hungarian, Scandinavian languages and Spanish, ''Andrea'' is a feminine name. Masculine forms are [[Andrej]], [[Ond\u0159ej]], [[Andrzej]], An\u017ee, [[Andrew]], [[Andreas (disambiguation)|Andreas]], [[Andr\u00e1s]], Andreo, [[Andres (disambiguation)|Andr\u00e9s]], [[Anders]], Andries or [[Andre (disambiguation)|Andre]].\n* In [[Albanian language|Albanian]] ''Andrea'' is a masculine name; its native form is [[Endri]].\n* In [[Romansh language|Romansh]] ''Andrea'' is also a masculine name.\n* In Italian, ''Andrea'' is a primarily<ref>[https://books.google.it/books?id=zLc9AAAAYAAJ Dizionario della lingua italiana \u2013 Volume VII, p. 529]</ref> masculine name.\n* In [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] Andrea is used as the feminine form of \"Andrei\".\n* In [[Croatia]], [[Serbia]] and [[Slovenia]], ''Andrea'' is a feminine name; ''Andreja'' can be used as female name, while ''Andrija'', ''Andro'' and ''Andrej'' are masculine forms. The only exception is [[Istria]], where Andrea is a male name.\n* In [[Romania]] ''[[Andreea]]'' is a feminine name and it is written with an extra \"e\". However, the feminine variation ''Andrea'' is also used. Andrea as [[etymon]] means ''knitting needle'' in [[Romanian language|Romanian]]. [[Andrei (given name)|Andrei]] is the masculine form.\n* ''Andr\u00e9a'' is a Brazilian Portuguese form of Andrea also used in Portugal along with ''Andreia''.\n* In [[Dutch language|Dutch]], ''Andrea'' is used as a female name, although the variant ''Andr\u00e9e'' is found in French.\n*In [[Spanish language|Spanish]], ''Andrea'' and a variation spelled ''Andressa'' are used as female variants for ''Andreo'' and ''Andr\u00e9s''. \n**In [[Basque language|Basque]], ''Andrea'' and ''Andere'' exist as female names. Two [[etymon]]s merge in the former: the most widespread form with a Greek root, 'man', and the [[Aquitanian language|Basque-Aquitanian]] ancient form \"andere(a)\", present-day \"andere(a)\" and \"andre(a)\", 'madam', 'lady' (used mainly as title, e.g. \"Andramari\", 'Lady/Virgin Mary'), as opposed to \"jaun\", 'lord'. In popular usage it can ultimately mean 'adult woman'.\n** In [[Catalan language|Catalan]], Andrea is used as the feminine form of \"Andreu\".\n\n== Notable people ==\n\n<!--PLEASE DO NOT ADD NAMES UNLESS THEY ALREADY HAVE WIKIPEDIA ARTICLES. THANKS!-->\n\n=== Women ===\n* [[Andrea Alf\u00f6ldi]] (born 1964), Hungarian race walker\n* [[Andrea Allan]] (born 1946), American actress\n* [[Andrea Anders]] (born 1975), American actress\n* [[Andrea Armstrong]] (born 1982), former American collegiate basketball player\n* [[Andrea \u00c1vila]] (born 1970), Argentine long and triple jumper\n* [[Andrea Baker]], American actress\n* [[Andrea Barber]] (born 1976), American actress\n* [[Andrea Barthwell]] (born 1953), American federal civil servant and Illinois political hopeful\n* [[Andrea Berg]] (born 1966), German singer \n* [[Andrea Berg (volleyball)|Andrea Berg]] (born 1981), German volleyball player\n* [[Andrea Borrell]] (born 1963), Cuban basketball player\n* [[Andrea Bowen]] (born 1990), American actress\n* [[Andrea Brown]] (born 1974), American singer\n* [[Andrea Brillantes]] (born 2003), Filipina actress\n* [[Andrea Canning]] (born 1972), Canadian-American broadcast journalist\n* [[Andrea \u010ce\u0161kov\u00e1]] (born 1971), Czech MEP\n* [[Andrea Corr]] (born 1974), Irish musician\n* [[Andrea Demetriades]] (born 1983), Australian actress\n* [[Andrea Demirovi\u0107]] (born 1985), Montenegrin singer\n* [[Andrea Dewar]] (born 1979), Canadian water polo player\n* [[Andrea Dworkin]] (1946\u20132005), American radical feminist and writer\n* [[Andrea Echeverri]] (born 1965), Colombian singer and guitarist, lead singer of the rock band [[Aterciopelados]]\n* [[Andreea Ehritt-Vanc]] (born 1973), Romanian tennis player\n* [[Andrea Farkas]] (born 1969), Hungarian handball goalkeeper\n* [[Andrea Feldman]] (1948-1972), American actress\n* [[Andrea Fioroni]] (born 1969), Argentine field hockey player\n* [[Andrea Fischer]] (born 1960), German politician\n* [[Andrea Ghez]] (born 1965), American astronomer\n* [[Andrea Glass]] (born 1976), German tennis player\n* [[Andrea Gibson]] (born 1975), spoken word artist and activist\n*[[Andrea Gyarmati]] (born 1954), Hungarian swimmer\n* [[Andrea Hall]] (born 1947), American soap opera actress\n* [[Andrea Hayes]] (born 1969), American backstroke swimmer\n* [[Andr\u00e9a Henriques]] (born 1980), Brazilian water polo player\n* [[Andrea Hlav\u00e1\u010dkov\u00e1]] (born 1986), Czech tennis player\n* [[Andrea van den Hurk]] (born 1979), Dutch tennis player\n* [[Andrea Robinson (sommelier)|Andrea Immer Robinson]] (born 1964), Master Sommelier and Dean of Wine Studies at the French Culinary Institute\n* [[Andrea Jaeger]] (born 1965), American former tennis player\n* [[Andrea Jeremiah]] (born 1985), Indian Tamil playback singer, film actress and a model.\n* [[A. J. Cook]] (born 1978), Canadian actress\n* [[Andrea Jung]] (born 1959), business executive\n* [[Andrea King]] (1919\u20132003), American actress\n* [[Andrea Kom\u0161i\u0107]] (born 1996), Croatian alpine skier\n* [[Andrea Koppel]] (born 1963), American news correspondent\n* [[Andrea Lau]] (born 1947), German actress\n* [[Andrea Leeds]] (1914\u20131984), American actress\n* [[Andrea Lehotsk\u00e1]] (born 1981), Slovak television hostess, actress, and top model.\n* [[Andrea Leki\u0107]] (born 1987), Serbian handball player\n* [[Andrea Levy]] (1956-2019), British author\n* [[Andrea Lewis]] (born 1985), Canadian actress\n* [[Andrea Libman]] (Born 1984), Canadian Voice Actress\n* [[Andrea Lowe]] (born 1975), British actress\n* [[Andrea Martin]] (born 1947), actress and comedian\n* [[Andrea Mason]] (born 1968), Australian politician\n* [[Andrea Mayr]] (born 1979), Austrian long-distance runner\n* [[Andrea McArdle]] (born 1963), American singer and actress\n* [[Andrea Mitchell]] (born 1946), American news correspondent\n* [[Andrea Moody]] (born 1978), Canadian swimmer\n* [[Andrea Murez]] (born 1992), Israeli-American Olympic swimmer for Israel\n* [[Andrea Newman]] (1938\u20132019), British author\n* [[Andrea Olsen]] (born 1961), American politician\n* [[Andrea Petkovic]] (born 1987), Glass's German compatriot and tennis player but she was born in [[Tuzla]], [[Bosnia]].\n* [[Andreea Raducan]] (born 1983), Romanian gymnast\n* [[Andrea Russett]] (born 1996), American actress\n* [[Andrea R\u016f\u017ei\u010dkov\u00e1]] (born 1984), Slovak actress and model\n* [[Andrea Romano (voice director)|Andrea Romano]] (born 1955), American voice actress\n* [[Andrea Su\u00e1rez (Thai singer)|Andrea Su\u00e1rez]] (born 1979), Thai singer\n* [[Andrea Temesv\u00e1ri]] (born 1966), Hungarian former tennis player\n* [[Andrea Thompson]] (born 1960), American actress\n* [[Andrea T\u00f3th]] (born 1980), Hungarian water polo player\n* [[Andrea True]] (born 1943), Porn actress and singer\n* [[Andrea Yates]] (born 1964), American defendant in a notorious filicide case\n* [[Andrea Zollo]] (born 1975), American singer\n* [[Andrea Zonn]] (born 1969), American singer and musician\n* [[Andrea Zsadon]], (born 1946) Hungarian soprano\n* [[Andrea 