] 'Most Wanted' website. Property of Kulturhistorisches Museum in Magdeburg, Germany (formerly the Kaiser-Friedrich Museum)<ref>{{cite web|title=Most Wanted: Works of Art|url=https://www.monumentsmenfoundation.org/intl/de/join-the-hunt/most-wanted-works-of-art|website=www.monumentsmenfoundation.org|publisher=Monuments Men Foundation|accessdate=5 August 2017|language=de}}</ref> || inestimable || missing\n|-\n| [[File:Gustav Klimt, 1907, Adele Bloch-Bauer I, Neue Galerie New York.jpg|200px]] || ''[[Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I]]'' by [[Gustav Klimt]] || 1940s || [[Austria]] || ''Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I'' is a 1907 painting by [[Gustav Klimt]]. According to press reports it was sold for US$135 million to [[Ronald Lauder]] for his [[Neue Galerie New York]] in June 2006, which made it at that time the [[List of most expensive paintings|most expensive painting]] for about 4 months.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vogel |first=Carol |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/19/arts/design/19klim.html |title=Lauder Pays $135 Million, a Record, for a Klimt Portrait|work=The New York Times|date=June 19, 2006 |accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> It has been on display at the gallery since July 2006. Klimt took three years to complete the painting. It measures 138&nbsp;cm \u00d7 138&nbsp;cm and is made of oil and gold on canvas, showing elaborate and complex ornamentation as seen in [[Jugendstil]]. Klimt was a member of the [[Vienna Secession]], a group of artists that broke away from the traditional way of painting. Adele Bloch-Bauer, in her will, asked her husband to donate the Klimt paintings to the [[\u00d6sterreichische Galerie Belvedere|Austrian State Gallery]] upon his death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adele.at/Klage_von__Dr__Stefan_Gulner_m/Vorgelegte_Urkunden/Testament_vom_19_1_1923_von_Ad/testament_vom_19_1_1923_von_ad.html |title=Last Will 1923 |publisher=Adele.at |date=January 19, 1923 |accessdate=May 15, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531045404/http://www.adele.at/Klage_von__Dr__Stefan_Gulner_m/Vorgelegte_Urkunden/Testament_vom_19_1_1923_von_Ad/testament_vom_19_1_1923_von_ad.html |archive-date=May 31, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  She died in 1925 from meningitis. When the Nazis took over [[Austria]], her widowed husband had to flee to Switzerland. His property, including the Klimt paintings, was confiscated. In his 1945 testament, Bloch-Bauer designated his nephew and nieces, including [[Maria Altmann]], as the inheritors of his estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arthistory.about.com/od/klim1/a/blochbauerklimt.htm |title=Bloch-Bauer 1945 testament |publisher=Arthistory.about.com |accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> || $135,000,000 || Returned to [[Maria Altmann]], niece of Adele Bloch-Bauer. See main article [[Republic of Austria v. Altmann]]\n|-\n| [[File:Raphael missing.jpg|200px]] || [[Portrait of a Young Man (Raphael)|''Portrait of a Young Man'']] by [[Raphael]] || 1940s || [[Poland]] || ''Portrait of a Young Man'' is a painting in oil on [[panel painting|panel]], probably from 1513 to 1514, by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[High Renaissance]] [[Old Master]] painter and architect Raffaello Sanzio da Urbino better known simply as [[Raphael]].<ref name=\"houpt49\">Houpt, Simon ''et al.'' (2006). ''Museum of the Missing,'' p. 49.</ref>  The painting was plundered by the [[Nazi]]s in [[Poland]]. The subject's identity is unverified, but many scholars have traditionally regarded it as Raphael's [[self-portrait]]. The facial features are perceived by specialists as compatible with, if not clearly identical to, the only undoubted self-portrait by Raphael in his [[fresco]] ''[[The School of Athens]]'' at the Vatican, identified as such by [[Vasari]]. If it is a self-portrait, no hint is given of Raphael's profession; the portrait shows a richly dressed and \"confidently-poised\" young man.<ref>Jones, Roger ''et al.'' (1983). ''Raphael'', p. 170\u2013171.</ref>  In recent times, a book about [[Nazi plunder]] by [[Lynn H. Nicholas]] and a documentary film by the same title, ''[[The Rape of Europa (book)|The Rape of Europa]]'', suggested that if the painting were to reappear today, it would be worth in excess of US$100M.|| $100,000,000<ref>[[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]: [https://www.pbs.org/therapeofeuropa/  ''The Rape of Europa.''], 2006 film, aired November 24, 2008.</ref>|| Falsely reported to have been found 1 August 2012, the location is still unknown.\n|-\n| [[File:Jean Metzinger, 1913, En Canot, oil on canvas, 146 x 114 cm, missing or destroyed.jpg|200px]] || ''[[En Canot]]'', by [[Jean Metzinger]] || c. 1936 || [[Kronprinzenpalais]], [[National Gallery (Berlin)|Nationalgalerie]], Berlin || ''En Canot'' (shown here in black and white) was exhibited at the Kronprinzenpalais, Nationalgalerie, Berlin, where it had been housed since 1927. The work was acquired by the Nationalgalerie in 1936 (on deposit by the Ministerium f\u00fcr Wissenschaft, Kunst und Volksbildung), where it was placed on display in Room 5. It was later confiscated by the Nazis around 1936, displayed at the [[Degenerate Art Exhibition]] ([[Degenerate Art|Entartete Kunst]]) in Munich and other cities, 1937\u201338, and has been missing ever since || $2,400,000 || Missing, presumed destroyed\n|-\n|}\n{{expand section|date=February 2012}}\n\n==Recovered==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Painting !! Title, Artist !! Date stolen !!  Date recovered !! Location of theft !! Details !! Estimated value \n|-\n| [[File:Mona Lisa, by Leonardo da Vinci, from C2RMF retouched.jpg|200px]] || ''[[Mona Lisa]]'' by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] || August 21, 1911 || 1913 || [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre]], Paris || {{see|Mona Lisa#Theft and vandalism}} Now in the Mus\u00e9e du Louvre in Paris. The painting's continued and increasing fame was heightened when it was stolen.<ref name=\"Stoner-PBS\">{{cite news|title=Theft of the Mona Lisa|url=https://www.pbs.org/treasuresoftheworld/a_nav/mona_nav/main_monafrm.html|publisher=Stoner Productions via Public Broadcasting Service (PBS)|accessdate=October 24, 2009}}</ref> The Louvre was closed for an entire week to aid the investigation.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Mona Lisa was finally found|url=http://zavok.com/portfolio-item/moaning-sharon-mona-lisa-dada-pastiche-painting/|accessdate=14 April 2001}}</ref> Recovered after the thief, [[Vincenzo Peruggia]], attempted to sell it.|| Assessed in 1962 at $100 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120201/jsp/frontpage/story_15077581.jsp|title=Louvre in India, minus ''Mona Lisa''|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Adjusted for inflation it would be worth $782 million today. \n|-\n| [[File:CaravaggioJeromeValletta.jpg|200px]] || [[Saint Jerome Writing (Caravaggio, Valletta)|''Saint Jerome Writing'']] by [[Caravaggio]] || December 29, 1984 || August 4, 1988 || [[St. John's Co-Cathedral]], [[Valletta]] || Damaged after the burglars cut it out of its frame, and restored in 1990. ||\n|-\n| <!---Do not add the image as it is still under copyright, per WP:NFLISTS---> || ''[[Woman-Ochre]]'' by [[Willem de Kooning]] || November 27, 1985 || 2017 || [[University of Arizona Museum of Art]], [[Tucson, Arizona]], U.S.|| Cut out of its frame shortly after the museum opened that day. Sketches of a couple believed to be responsible were distributed widely but they were never identified; the couple in whose home the painting was found after their deaths in the 2010s has been suspected. Currently being restored.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryman|first=Anne|title=Who stole the $100M masterpiece? Clues emerge in year since recovery of Willem de Kooning painting|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-best-reads/2018/08/01/art-heist-woman-ochre-clues-emerge-willem-de-kooning-painting-recovered/789652002/|newspaper=[[The Arizona Republic]]|date=August 1, 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018}}</ref>\n|| Insured for $400,000 at the time of theft; however the market value of similar de Kooning works had increased to above $100 million by the time it was recovered and the museum believes it is worth $160 million today  \n|-\n| [[File:Le Gar\u00e7on au gilet rouge, par Paul C\u00e9zanne, FWN 496.jpg|200px]] || ''[[The Boy in the Red Vest]]'' by [[Paul C\u00e9zanne]] || February 10, 2008 || April 12, 2012<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17687963 | work=BBC News | title=Stolen Cezanne found by Serbian police | date=April 12, 2012}}</ref>|| [[Foundation E.G. B\u00fchrle]], [[Z\u00fcrich]], Switzerland || An 1894/95<ref name=\"EG BUHRLE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buehrle.ch/works_detail.php?lang=en&id_pic=55|title=Foundation E.G. B\u00fchrle Collection - Welcome to our Website|work=buehrle.ch}}</ref> painting ([[Lionello Venturi|Venturi]] 681) depicting a boy in traditional Italian attire. [[Art theft#Emile B.C3.BChrle Foundation in Zurich .282008.29|Stolen]] along with three other pieces.<ref name=\"news.com.au\">{{cite news| url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,23203876-663,00.html |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia | title=Reward for $180m Zurich art heist bandits | date=February 13, 2008}}</ref> It was the museum's most valuable painting. Recovered in Serbia. || $91,000,000<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/20/world/europe/20zurich.html 2 Paintings Stolen From Zurich Museum Didn\u2019t Get Far]\". NY Times, February 20, 2008</ref> \n|-\n| [[File:Edgar Germain Hilaire Degas 053.jpg|200px]] \n|| ''[[Count Lepic and His Daughters]]'' by [[Edgar Degas]] \n|| February 10, 2008 \n|| April 2012\n|| [[Foundation E.G. B\u00fchrle]], [[Z\u00fcrich]], Switzerland \n|| An 1870 painting [[Art theft#Emile B.C3.BChrle Foundation in Zurich .282008.29|stolen]] from [[Foundation E.G. B\u00fchrle]] in [[Z\u00fcrich]], Switzerland.<ref name=\"news.com.au\"/> Four paintings were stolen altogether with two of them being returned in 2008. Degas also painted Viscount [[Ludovic-Napol\u00e9on Lepic]] in the 1875 painting [[Place de la Concorde (painting)|''Place de la Concorde'']]. Recovered in Serbia.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1578325/Paintings-worth-85-million-stolen-in-Zurich.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph  | first=Henry | last=Samuel | title=Paintings worth \u00a385 million stolen in Zurich | date=February 11, 2008}}</ref> \n|| Part of a $162.5 million art heist<ref>Interpol: [http://www.interpol.com/Public/News/2008/woa20080211.asp Four masterpieces stolen from Zurich museum] (ref.: 2008/5583)</ref><ref>Harnischfeger, Uta and Nicholas Kulish. [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/12/world/europe/12swiss.html At Zurich Museum, a Theft of 4 Masterworks]. ''The New York Times''. February 12, 2008. Retrieved April 21, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/culture/Stolen_Degas_recovered_damaged.html?cid=32566670|title=Stolen Degas recovered damaged|work=SWI Swissinfo.ch}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:The Scream.jpg|200px]] || ''[[The Scream]]'' (''Der Schrei der Natur'') by [[Edvard Munch]] <!-- Title / Artist -->\n|| 1994<br /> <small>and</small><br /> 2004 \n|| 1994<br /> <small>and</small><br /> 2006\n|| [[National Gallery, Oslo]] <br /> <small>and</small><br /> [[Munch Museum]], Oslo  <!--  Location of theft -->\n|| {{see|The Scream#Thefts}}\n''The Scream'' has been the target of several high-profile art thefts. In 1994, the version in the  [[National Gallery, Oslo]] was stolen. It was recovered several months later. In 2004, both ''The Scream'' and [[Madonna (Edvard Munch)|''Madonna'']] were stolen from the [[Munch Museum]].\n|| $110,000,000 \n|-\n| [[File:Rembrandt Harmensz. van Rijn - Selfportrait - Google Art Project.jpg|200px]] || ''Self-portrait with Beret and Gathered Shirt'' (\u2018stilus mediocris\u2019) by [[Rembrandt]] \n|| December 22, 2000\n|| 2005\n|| [[Nationalmuseum]], Stockholm \n||The small self-portrait on copper by Rembrandt was stolen from Nationalmuseum in Stockholm along with Renoir's ''A Young Parisienne'' and ''Conversation'' in an armed robbery in December 2000. It was recovered in Copenhagen. ''Conversation'' was recovered in Stockholm a few months after the robbery and ''A Young Parisienne'' was recovered in Los Angeles in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.codart.nl/news/89/ |publisher=Codart.nl |title=Rembrandt recovered! Self-portrait stolen from Nationalmuseum in Stockholm recovered in Copenhagen |date=16 September 2005 |accessdate=2014-01-19}}</ref>\n|| $37,000,000 \n|-\n|| \n|| ''Femme Assise'' by [[Henri Matisse]] \n|| July 1940\n|| 2012\n|| [[Paul Rosenberg (art dealer)|Paul Rosenberg]], Paris\n|| One of around 450 paintings looted from the collection of Paul Rosenberg by the [[Einsatzstab Reichsleiter Rosenberg|Einsatzstab Reichsleiter Rosenberg (ERR)]]. Missing for over 70 years, it was discovered in the Munich home of [[Cornelius Gurlitt (art collector)|Cornelius Gurlitt]] in 2012 and later returned to Rosenberg's heirs.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eddy|first1=Melissa|title=Matisse From Gurlitt Collection Is Returned to Jewish Art Dealer\u2019s Heirs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/16/arts/international/matisse-gurlitt-collection-femme-assise-seated-woman.html|accessdate=21 May 2015|work=The New York Times|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> \n|| \n|-\n|[[File:Zeegezicht bij Scheveningen - s0416M1990 - Van Gogh Museum.jpg|200px]]\n|''[[View of the Sea at Scheveningen]]'' by [[Vincent van Gogh]]\n|December 7, 2002\n|September 30, 2016\n|[[Van Gogh Museum]], Amsterdam, Netherlands\n|Recovered in Naples.\n|Part of a $30,000,000 art heist.  \n|-\n|[[File:Van Gogh - Die Kirche von Nuenen mit Kirchg\u00e4ngern.jpeg|200px]]\n|''[[Congregation Leaving the Reformed Church in Nuenen]]'' by [[Vincent van Gogh]]\n|December 7, 2002\n|September 30, 2016\n|[[Van Gogh Museum]], Amsterdam, Netherlands\n|Recovered in Naples.\n|Part of a $30,000,000 art heist. \n|-\n|[[File:The Chorus 1876 Edgar Degas.jpg|200px]]\n|''[[Les Choristes]]'' by [[Edgar Degas]]\n|2009\n|February 2018\n|[[Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], Paris, France (stolen while on loan to [[Mus\u00e9e Cantini]], Marseille)\n|Recovered outside Paris.\n|\u20ac800,000 \n|-\n| [[File:Gustav Klimt 061.jpg|200px]] \n| ''[[Portrait of a Lady (Klimt)|Portrait of a Lady]]'' by [[Gustav Klimt]] \n| February 22, 1997 \n| December 2019\n| [[Galleria Ricci-Oddi]], Piacenza, Italy || Believed to have been stolen shortly before a special exhibition was planned at the gallery in Piacenza. Recovered after 23 years hidden in the gallery wall in Piacenza.\n|  \u20ac60 million<ref>{{cite web |title=Stolen Klimt mystery 'solved' by gardener in Italy |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50743143 |website=BBC News |accessdate=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Vincent Willem van Gogh 054.jpg|200px]]\n| ''The Gardener'' {{nowrap|(or, ''Young Peasant'')}} by [[Vincent van Gogh]]\n| May 19, 1998\n|1998\n| [[Galleria Nazionale d'Arte Moderna]], Rome\n| Theft included two paintings by Van Gogh and one by Paul Cezanne. Recovered by the [[Carabinieri Art Squad]] a few weeks later.\n| Three paintings estimated combined value: $34 million\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Law|Visual arts}}\n*[[Art Recovery Group]]\n*[[Art theft]]\n*[[Commission for Looted Art in Europe]]\n*[[Looted art]]\n*[[Lost artworks]]\n*[[Monuments Men]] \u2014 Monuments, Fine Arts, and Archives program\n*[[Nazi plunder]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Stolen paintings}}\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/investigate/violent-crime/art-theft FBI: Art Theft]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131106035930/http://www.met.police.uk/artandantiques/ Art and Antiques Unit \u2013 New Scotland Yard]\n*[http://www.artloss.com/en The Art Loss Register] The world's largest database of stolen art \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140105203258/http://stolenmasterpieces.com/ Stolen Masterpieces - Famous Stolen Oil Paintings]\n*{{cite web|title=Most Wanted: Works of Art|url=https://www.monumentsmenfoundation.org/intl/de/join-the-hunt/most-wanted-works-of-art|website=Monuments Men Foundation|language=de}}\n\n[[Category:Art crime|Stolen paintings]]\n[[Category:Art thieves| ]]\n[[Category:Stolen works of art| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of paintings|Stolen paintings]]\n", "name_user": "Aarondyck", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_stolen_paintings"}
{"title_page": "OFB (group)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = OFB\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[London]]\n| genre            = [[British_hip_hop#UK_drill|UK drill]]\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Harlem Spartans]]\n| website          = \n| current_members  = [[Headie One]]<br>[[RV (rapper)|RV]]<br>Bandokay<br>Lowkey<br>Suspect\n| alias            = Original Farm Boys\n}}\n\n{{short description|UK drill music group}}\n\n'''OFB''', also known as '''Original Farm Boys''', is a British [[drill music|drill]] group based in [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[North London]]. OFB is among one of the most prominent UK drill groups.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|title=UK drill rappers OFB: 'No one helps us round here. Music is the only way'|last=Thapar|first=Ciaran|date=2019-09-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217134655/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|archive-date=2019-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|title=The 20 best albums of 2019|last=Dazed|date=2019-12-11|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215164722/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|title=The Drop: The Best UK Drill of November 2019|date=2019-11-14|website=Passion of the Weiss|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182618/https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Headie One]] (formerly Headz) and [[RV (rapper)|RV]] (formerly Young RV) are among the most prominent members of the group. They were both originally rappers in Star Gang, a [[road rap]] group from the 2000s and split-off from the [[Tottenham Mandem]] gang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|title=Heart of a lion: the rise of Headie One|website=The Face|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108132845/https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|archive-date=2019-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref> RV and Headie One have frequently collaborated with each other, including co-releasing the mixtapes ''Sticks & Stones'' (2016) and ''Drillers x Trappers'' (2017).<ref name=\"nme match day\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|title=Watch RV and Headie One's football-themed video for 'Match Day'|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=21 March 2019|work=[[NME]]|access-date=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324030654/https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|archive-date=24 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2018, Headie One released his solo mixtape, ''The One''. The mixtape included the song \"Know Better\" featuring [[RV (rapper)|RV]], which became an \"underground hit\". This was followed by another solo mixtape, ''The One Two'', in June 2018, which entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|title=The One Two|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119182750/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBandokay, DoubleLz, and SJ form a sub-group within OFB, initially using the name Y.OFB (Young OFB) signifying their status as younger members of the group, before later dropping the \"Y.\" and co-opting the \"OFB\" prefix older members of the group used.<ref name=\":2\" /> OFB rapper Bandokay, whos real name is Kemani Duggan, is the son of [[Death of Mark Duggan|Mark Duggan]], a British man from Broadwater Farm who was shot dead by police in 2011, the result of which led to the [[2011 England riots|2011 England Riots]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Bandokay credited music for keeping him away from crime, and stated his desire to be away from police as a motivator:<ref name=\":0\" /><blockquote>Whenever [the police] see me, they stop me, I get what they\u2019re trying to do \u2013 they\u2019re trying to take weapons. But I know they purposely stop me more than anyone else. They know who I am. They know who my dad is. So that\u2019s why I\u2019m trying to go through music and do something positive, so they don\u2019t have nothing to say about me.</blockquote>Bandokay credited fellow OFB rapper Headie One as a major influence, as well as UK drill group [[67 (rap group)|67]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2019, Headie One released \"18Hunna\", featuring [[Dave (rapper)|Dave]], which entered the UK chart at number 6 - the highest a drill artist has ever charted.<ref name=\"Headie One\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|title=Headie One|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=30 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121614/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Top40\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|title=Who is Headie One and what is the '18 Hunna' challenge?|date=15 January 2019|website=[[The Official Big Top 40]]|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121104/https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following RV's release from prison,<ref name=\"scan\">{{Cite web|url=https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|title=What Do You Mean You Haven't Heard Of... RV?|date=12 March 2019|website=[[SCAN (newspaper)|SCAN]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107193910/https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|archive-date=7 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> on 22 March 2019, RV and Headie One released a third mixtape called ''Drillers x Trappers II''.<ref name=\"complex\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|title=Headie One And RV Return With 'Drillers x Trappers II' Mixtape|last=Oke|first=Tobi|date=22 March 2019|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=26 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326125431/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|archive-date=26 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 21.<ref name=\"drillers charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ \"Drillers and Trappers 2\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330143441/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ |date=2019-03-30 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">30 March</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> \"Match Day\", the first single from the mixtape, entered the Singles Chart at number 86.<ref name=\"match day charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ \"match day &#x7C; full Official Chart History\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107200729/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ |date=2019-11-07 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 November</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> He publicly revealed his face for the first time in the music video \"Why Always Me\".<ref name=\"the face\">{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|title=Bally On Me: Why UK drill rappers cover their faces|website=[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]|language=en-gb|access-date=24 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509164715/https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GRM brand new\">{{Cite news|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|title=Premiere: RV Makes Big Return With \"Brand New/Why Always Me\" Visuals|last=Wynter|first=Courtney|date=28 February 2019|work=[[GRM Daily]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608221347/http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|archive-date=8 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the OFB released their first collective mixtape titled \"Frontstreet\", named after a road in Broadwater Farm that locals call \"Front Street\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> [[Dazed|Dazed Digital]] called the mixtape \"one of the best British debuts of the decade\".<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2019, following the release of (OFB member) SJ's \"Youngest In Charge\", it was revealed SJ was currently facing trial for a murder charge and had been arrested.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|title=The Ones: Bandokay and Double Lz's \"Mad About Bars\"|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLike many other drill groups, OFB has had its songs taken down by YouTube at request of the [[Metropolitan Police Service|metropolitan police]]. In 2019, OFB's own YouTube channel was also taken down, before later being reinstated the next day. Bandokay stated they were trying to clean up their music in order to avoid takedowns.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Members ==\nThe list below includes confirmed members of OFB:{{div col}}\n* Akz\n* Bandokay<ref name=\":0\" /> (son of [[Mark Duggan]])\n* Bradz \n* Dee One<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|title=OFB's Dee One Delivers Cold 'Next Up? Freestyle|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Dezzie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|title=Dezzie unveils brand-new 'Bad Breed' visuals|website=Link Up Tv|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191453/https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Double Lz<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Dsavvv\n* Headie One<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|title=The New New: 14 U.K. Rappers You Should Know - XXL|last=Rathod|first=Nikita|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Izzpot<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-izzpot-free-s|title=OFB's Izzpot drops visuals for new track \"Free S\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n* JS<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|title=OFB's JS Releases \"Young Rich\" Visuals|website=www.mixtapemadness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kash<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/kash-you-alright|title=OFB's Kash asks \"You Alright?\" in latest video|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191455/http://grmdaily.com/video/kash-you-alright|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kush<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-kush-no-biggie|title=OFB's Kush provides hard tune \"No Biggie\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-kush-no-biggie|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Lowkey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plugsville.com/drillers-x-trappers-ii-rv-headie-one-mixtape-match-day/|title=Drillers x Trappers II: RV and Headie One release mixtape and 'Match Day'|date=2019-03-22|website=Plugsville|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215192953/https://www.plugsville.com/drillers-x-trappers-ii-rv-headie-one-mixtape-match-day/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Munie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/ofb-munie-lightwork-freestyle-new-song-listen/|title=The Ones: OFB Munie's \"Lightwork Freestyle\"|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191452/https://pitchfork.com/levels/ofb-munie-lightwork-freestyle-new-song-listen/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* RV<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/knife-attackers-use-youtube-to-issue-death-threats-from-prison-rxq9pkqll|title=Knife attackers use YouTube to issue death threats from prison|last=Shingi\u00a0Mararike|first=Tom Harper and|date=2019-03-10|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en|issn=0956-1382|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824194613/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/knife-attackers-use-youtube-to-issue-death-threats-from-prison-rxq9pkqll|archive-date=2019-08-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* SJ<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Skat<ref>{{Cite \nweb|url=https://versus.uk.com/2018/10/headie-one-links-skat-ofb-collab-water/|title=Headie One Links Up with Skat for OFB Collab, \"Water\"|date=2018-10-15|website=VERSUS|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191455/https://versus.uk.com/2018/10/headie-one-links-skat-ofb-collab-water/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Zilla<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/munie-zilla-cant-save-these-shots|title=OFB's Munie & Zilla join forces for \"Can't Save These Shots\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/http://grmdaily.com/video/munie-zilla-cant-save-these-shots|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Tottenham]]\n[[Category:London street gangs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = OFB\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[London]]\n| genre            = [[British_hip_hop#UK_drill|UK drill]]\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Harlem Spartans]]\n| website          = \n| current_members  = [[Headie One]]<br>[[RV (rapper)|RV]]<br>Bandokay<br>Lowkey<br>\n| alias            = Original Farm Boys\n}}\n\n{{short description|UK drill music group}}\n\n'''OFB''', also known as '''Original Farm Boys''', is a British [[drill music|drill]] group based in [[Broadwater Farm]], [[Tottenham]], [[North London]]. OFB is among one of the most prominent UK drill groups.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|title=UK drill rappers OFB: 'No one helps us round here. Music is the only way'|last=Thapar|first=Ciaran|date=2019-09-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217134655/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/06/uk-drill-rappers-ofb-no-one-helps-us-round-here-music-is-the-only-way|archive-date=2019-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|title=The 20 best albums of 2019|last=Dazed|date=2019-12-11|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215164722/https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/47070/1/the-20-best-albums-of-2019|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|title=The Drop: The Best UK Drill of November 2019|date=2019-11-14|website=Passion of the Weiss|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215182618/https://www.passionweiss.com/2019/11/14/the-drop-the-best-uk-drill-of-november-2019/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Headie One]] (formerly Headz) and [[RV (rapper)|RV]] (formerly Young RV) are among the most prominent members of the group. They were both originally rappers in Star Gang, a [[road rap]] group from the 2000s and split-off from the [[Tottenham Mandem]] gang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|title=Heart of a lion: the rise of Headie One|website=The Face|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108132845/https://theface.com/music/headie-one-drill-rap-volume-4-issue-001|archive-date=2019-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref> RV and Headie One have frequently collaborated with each other, including co-releasing the mixtapes ''Sticks & Stones'' (2016) and ''Drillers x Trappers'' (2017).<ref name=\"nme match day\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|title=Watch RV and Headie One's football-themed video for 'Match Day'|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=21 March 2019|work=[[NME]]|access-date=9 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324030654/https://www.nme.com/news/music/rv-headie-one-football-themed-video-match-day-2465089|archive-date=24 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2018, Headie One released his solo mixtape, ''The One''. The mixtape included the song \"Know Better\" featuring [[RV (rapper)|RV]], which became an \"underground hit\". This was followed by another solo mixtape, ''The One Two'', in June 2018, which entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|title=The One Two|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119182750/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/the-one-two/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBandokay, DoubleLz, and SJ form a sub-group within OFB, initially using the name Y.OFB (Young OFB) signifying their status as younger members of the group, before later dropping the \"Y.\" and co-opting the \"OFB\" prefix older members of the group used.<ref name=\":2\" /> OFB rapper Bandokay, whos real name is Kemani Duggan, is the son of [[Death of Mark Duggan|Mark Duggan]], a British man from Broadwater Farm who was shot dead by police in 2011, the result of which led to the [[2011 England riots|2011 England Riots]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Bandokay credited music for keeping him away from crime, and stated his desire to be away from police as a motivator:<ref name=\":0\" /><blockquote>Whenever [the police] see me, they stop me, I get what they\u2019re trying to do \u2013 they\u2019re trying to take weapons. But I know they purposely stop me more than anyone else. They know who I am. They know who my dad is. So that\u2019s why I\u2019m trying to go through music and do something positive, so they don\u2019t have nothing to say about me.</blockquote>Bandokay credited fellow OFB rapper Headie One as a major influence, as well as UK drill group [[67 (rap group)|67]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2019, Headie One released \"18Hunna\", featuring [[Dave (rapper)|Dave]], which entered the UK chart at number 6 - the highest a drill artist has ever charted.<ref name=\"Headie One\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|title=Headie One|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=30 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121614/https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52982/headie-one/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Top40\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|title=Who is Headie One and what is the '18 Hunna' challenge?|date=15 January 2019|website=[[The Official Big Top 40]]|publisher=[[Global (company)|Global]]|accessdate=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121104/https://www.bigtop40.com/features/headie-one-18-hunna-challenge-age-instagram/|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following RV's release from prison,<ref name=\"scan\">{{Cite web|url=https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|title=What Do You Mean You Haven't Heard Of... RV?|date=12 March 2019|website=[[SCAN (newspaper)|SCAN]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107193910/https://scan.lancastersu.co.uk/2019/03/12/what-do-you-mean-you-havent-heard-of-rv/|archive-date=7 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> on 22 March 2019, RV and Headie One released a third mixtape called ''Drillers x Trappers II''.<ref name=\"complex\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|title=Headie One And RV Return With 'Drillers x Trappers II' Mixtape|last=Oke|first=Tobi|date=22 March 2019|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|access-date=26 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326125431/https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/headie-one-rv-dxt-ii|archive-date=26 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 21.<ref name=\"drillers charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ \"Drillers and Trappers 2\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330143441/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/drillers-and-trappers-2/ |date=2019-03-30 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">30 March</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> \"Match Day\", the first single from the mixtape, entered the Singles Chart at number 86.<ref name=\"match day charts\"><cite class=\"citation web\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ \"match day &#x7C; full Official Chart History\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107200729/https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/match-day/ |date=2019-11-07 }}. ''[[Official Charts Company]]''<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 November</span> 2019</span>.</cite></ref> He publicly revealed his face for the first time in the music video \"Why Always Me\".<ref name=\"the face\">{{Cite web|url=https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|title=Bally On Me: Why UK drill rappers cover their faces|website=[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]|language=en-gb|access-date=24 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509164715/https://theface.com/music/bally-on-me-why-uk-rappers-cover-their-faces|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GRM brand new\">{{Cite news|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|title=Premiere: RV Makes Big Return With \"Brand New/Why Always Me\" Visuals|last=Wynter|first=Courtney|date=28 February 2019|work=[[GRM Daily]]|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608221347/http://grmdaily.com/video/rv-brand-new-why-always-me|archive-date=8 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the OFB released their first collective mixtape titled \"Frontstreet\", named after a road in Broadwater Farm that locals call \"Front Street\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> [[Dazed|Dazed Digital]] called the mixtape \"one of the best British debuts of the decade\".<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2019, following the release of (OFB member) SJ's \"Youngest In Charge\", it was revealed SJ was currently facing trial for a murder charge and had been arrested.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|title=The Ones: Bandokay and Double Lz's \"Mad About Bars\"|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://pitchfork.com/levels/bandokay-double-lz-mad-about-bars-new-song-listen/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLike many other drill groups, OFB has had its songs taken down by YouTube at request of the [[Metropolitan Police Service|metropolitan police]]. In 2019, OFB's own YouTube channel was also taken down, before later being reinstated the next day. Bandokay stated they were trying to clean up their music in order to avoid takedowns.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Members ==\nThe list below includes confirmed members of OFB:{{div col}}\n* Akz\n* Bandokay<ref name=\":0\" /> (son of [[Mark Duggan]])\n* Bradz \n* Dee One<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|title=OFB's Dee One Delivers Cold 'Next Up? Freestyle|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/http://grmdaily.com/video/dee-one-next-up-freestyle|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Dezzie<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|title=Dezzie unveils brand-new 'Bad Breed' visuals|website=Link Up Tv|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191453/https://www.thelinkup.com/content/586/dezzie-unveils-brand-new-bad-breed-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Double Lz<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Dsavvv\n* Headie One<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|title=The New New: 14 U.K. Rappers You Should Know - XXL|last=Rathod|first=Nikita|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191451/https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/08/new-new-u-k-rappers-you-should-know/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Izzpot<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ofb-izzpot-free-s|title=OFB's Izzpot drops visuals for new track \"Free S\"|website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n* JS<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|title=OFB's JS Releases \"Young Rich\" Visuals|website=www.mixtapemadness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215191450/https://www.mixtapemadness.com/blog/videos/ofbs-js-releases-young-rich-visuals|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Kash<ref>{{Cite web|url=h